:09','',0,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/youtube.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(107,2,'2013-09-20 21:21:40','2013-09-20 21:21:40',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','services','','','2014-07-08 15:22:01','2014-07-08 22:22:01','',0,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/?p=107',11,'nav_menu_item','',0),(116,2,'2013-09-25 23:50:48','2013-09-25 23:50:48','<h1>Hotel de Zink</h1>\r\n<h2>IVSN’s Hotel de Zink provides emergency shelter for 15 adult men and women in Palo Alto</h2>\r\nIVSN’s Hotel de Zink is 15-bed emergency shelter program that alternates locations through congregations in Palo Alto and surrounding neighborhoods. The shelter is hosted at a different church each month, where volunteers set up nightly beds and serve home-cooked meals for homeless adults who would otherwise be forced to sleep in cars or on the streets.\r\n\r\nHotel de Zink is a unique and effective collaboration between InnVision Shelter Network, faith-based communities, and local volunteers. The shelter program was established in 1989 by Urban Ministries of Palo Alto, which merged with InnVision in 2002 and continued the agency’s legacy of serving homeless and low-income individuals in the Mid-Peninsula.\r\n\r\nClients may stay at Hotel de Zink for up to 90 days, which provides them with stability, safety, and a team of experienced staff working to help them become self-sufficient. Clients are expected to meet weekly with their case manager to work on individually-tailored goals, such as employment, housing, education, and mental health.\r\n<h4>Faith Communities Hosting Shelter Beds</h4>\r\nJanuary: <strong>Trinity Lutheran Church</strong>, 1295 Middlefield Road, Palo Alto\r\nFebruary: <strong>Wesley Methodist Church</strong>, 463 College Avenue, Palo Alto\r\nMarch: <strong>First Congregational Church</strong>, 1985 Lewis Road, Palo Alto\r\nApril: <strong>Church of Christ</strong>, 3373 Middlefield Road, Palo Alto\r\nMay: <strong>St. Mark’s Episcopal</strong>, 600 Colorado Avenue, Palo Alto\r\nJune: <strong>First Methodist Church</strong>, 625 Hamilton Avenue, Palo Alto\r\nJuly: <strong>First Presbyterian Church</strong>, 1140 Cowper Street., Palo Alto\r\nAugust: <strong>Christian Reformed Church</strong>, 687 Arastradero Road, Palo Alto\r\nSeptember: <strong>Unitarian Church</strong>, 505 E. Charleston Road, Palo Alto\r\nOctober: <strong>All Saints’ Episcopal Church</strong>, 555 Waverley Street, Palo Alto\r\nNovember: <strong>Menlo Park Presbyterian</strong>, 950 Santa Cruz Avenue, Menlo Park\r\nDecember: <strong>Friends Meeting</strong>, 957 Colorado Avenue, Palo Alto\r\n<h4>How to Get Shelter</h4>\r\nTo access shelter with Hotel de Zink, clients must visit the <a title=\"Opportunity Services Center\" href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/services/family-services/opportunity-services-center/\">Opportunity Services Center</a> to meet in-person with a case manager.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/services/family-services/opportunity-services-center/\">Opportunity Services Center</a>\r\n33 Encina Avenue\r\nPalo Alto, CA 94301\r\nPhone: (650) 853-8672\r\nHours: Mon-Fri, 8 am-4 pm','Hotel de Zink','','publish','closed','open','','hotel-de-zink','','','2013-12-18 14:48:52','2013-12-18 22:48:52','',35,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/?page_id=116',106,'page','',0),(117,2,'2013-09-25 23:51:13','2013-09-25 23:51:13',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','117','','','2015-09-02 20:59:37','2015-09-03 03:59:37','',35,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/?p=117',21,'nav_menu_item','',0),(119,2,'2013-09-25 23:57:31','2013-09-25 23:57:31','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-414\" src=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/services_family_housing_first-320x240.jpg\" alt=\"services_family_housing_first\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" />Housing First Program</h1>\r\n<h2>Housing First rapidly transitions people from homelessness into permanent housing.</h2>\r\nThrough Housing First, clients who are homeless but have a reliable income receive move-in assistance and shallow rent subsidies.\r\n\r\nBy providing financial assistance to move directly into permanent housing (accompanied by case management and supportive services), clients are able to <i>bypass</i> the shelter stay altogether. This model is not only fiscally efficient from an organizational standpoint, but also circumvents the psychological impact of short-term housing solutions, which can be particularly devastating for children.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the Housing First program helps preserve urgently needed shelter beds for those most in need.\r\n<h2>Eligibility</h2>\r\nTo qualify for Housing First, clients must be homeless, working or gaining reliable income, but earning less than 200% of the national poverty level. Families and individuals may receive up to $2,000 for move-in assistance, depending on income, and a 50% rent subsidy for up to six months. After securing permanent housing, clients receive follow-up case management to ensure their long-term success.\r\n\r\nFor questions about the Housing First program, contact Teresa Brown at (650) 315-3503 or <a href=\"mailto:tbrown@ivsn.org\">tbrown@ivsn.org</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Housing First Program','','publish','closed','open','','housing-first','','','2015-09-24 15:14:08','2015-09-24 22:14:08','',36,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/?page_id=119',105,'page','',0),(120,2,'2013-09-25 23:58:49','2013-09-25 23:58:49',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','120','','','2015-09-02 20:59:37','2015-09-03 03:59:37','',36,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/?p=120',24,'nav_menu_item','',0),(121,2,'2013-09-26 00:00:10','2013-09-26 00:00:10','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-419\" alt=\"writing\" src=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/services_homeless_woman_writing-320x212.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"212\" />Bridges Program</h1>\r\n<h2>IVSN’s Bridges Program promotes education and employment</h2>\r\nIVSN’s Bridges Program is designed specifically for clients who are going back to school and investing in opportunities that lead to sustainable careers — “bridging” the gap between education and employment.\r\n\r\nBridges provides transitional housing for formerly homeless individuals and families for 6 to 12 months while they establish residential stability.\r\n\r\nThe program is designed to assist individuals in attaining and maintaining self-sufficiency by obtaining job skills, increasing income and promoting financial literacy.\r\n<h2>Participation Requirements</h2>\r\nWhile in the Bridges program applicants must…\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Enroll in a program to advance education and/or reduce incurred debt</li>\r\n	<li>Save money each month</li>\r\n	<li>Meet with a Bridges Case Manager bi-weekly to work on case plan goals and objectives</li>\r\n	<li>Attend financial literacy and job development workshops</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Eligibility</h2>\r\nOnly current residents of IVSN’s shelter programs are eligible for the Bridges Program. Applicants must be working or volunteering in a career advancement activity, such as a vocational training program, state board exam preparation, or community college classes.\r\n<h2>Contact</h2>\r\nFor more information about the Bridges program, contact Teresa Brown at <a href=\"mailto:tbrown@ivsn.org\">tbrown@ivsn.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Bridges Program','','publish','closed','open','','bridges','','','2013-10-14 23:40:26','2013-10-14 23:40:26','',36,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/?page_id=121',104,'page','',0),(122,2,'2013-09-26 00:02:26','2013-09-26 00:02:26','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-413\" alt=\"services_alumni_association_balloon_toss\" src=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/services_alumni_association_balloon_toss-320x211.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"211\" />Alumni Association</h1>\r\n<h2>What is the Alumni Association?</h2>\r\nThe Alumni Association offers support and services to graduates from all of InnVision Shelter Network’s programs and shelters.\r\n\r\nOur mission is to facilitate supportive relationships between current and former clients, such that we may motivate, encourage, and guide each other on the path to self-sufficiency.\r\n<h2>Who Can Join the Alumni Association?</h2>\r\nEligible alumni include all graduates from InnVision Shelter Network’s transitional housing sites (both families and single adults), permanent supportive housing, and other housing programs.\r\n<h2>Opportunities for Alumni Involvement</h2>\r\n<strong>Attend Events &amp; Workshops:</strong> Meet fellow alumni at social/networking events throughout the year, such as the Summer BBQ or Annual Holiday Party.\r\n<strong>Volunteer:</strong> Give back to IVSN through done-in-a-day volunteer projects, such as sorting donations, painting the facility, or staging apartments for new families moving into the site.\r\n<strong>Share Your Story:</strong> Inspire current clients living at IVSN by sharing your own personal story or experience.\r\n<strong>Mentor and Support:</strong> Attend informal group sessions with alumni or currents clients to empower and support each other.\r\n<strong>Join the Leadership Team:</strong> Take a leadership role and attend monthly meetings to discuss future plans and the direction of the Alumni Association.\r\n<h2>Ready to Sign Up?</h2>\r\nComplete the form below, or contact the Alumni Coordinator at <a href=\"mailto:alumni@ivsn.org\">alumni@ivsn.org</a> or  (650) 685-5880 ext. 152.\r\n\r\n<a id=\"formAnchor1118747300\" name=\"form1118747300\"></a>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://www.formsite.com/include/form/embedManager.js?1118747300\"></script>\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\">// <![CDATA[\r\nEmbedManager.embed({\r\n	key: \"http://www.formsite.com/res/showFormEmbed?EParam=PyBo85CFjhEsbxUbMlcXKEmClzPPWKg6&#038;1118747300\",\r\n	width: \"100%\"\r\n});\r\n// ]]></script>\r\n<!-- Notes:\r\nTo control the width of the form, change width: \"100%\" to any number or percentage.\r\nTo pre-populate fields in the form or to use a custo