','2013-10-10 15:14:36','',0,'http://ivsn.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/youtube_button.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(431,12,'2013-10-11 19:44:49','2013-10-11 19:44:49','<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-432\" alt=\"Meisha\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Meisha-1024x719.jpg\" width=\"550\" height=\"386\" />\r\n\r\nMeisha and her daughter became homeless when a family member was diagnosed with Cystic Fibrosis, and the medical expenses exhausted their savings.\r\n\r\nThey came to InnVision Shelter Network’s transitional family shelter in Menlo Park. With the help of her case manager, Meisha was able to enroll in a Medical Assistant training program at a vocational college. She was accepted to InnVision Shelter Network’s Bridges Program, a special opportunity for clients going back to school, helping “bridge the gap” between education and employment.\r\n\r\nMeisha and her daughter moved from the shelter into a one-bedroom apartment. Throughout her year-long training course, InnVision Shelter Network subsidized a significant portion of the rent and helped find affordable child care for her daughter.\r\n\r\nAfter Meisha earned her credential, she landed her dream job as a Medical Assistant. Now that two years have passed, Meisha and her daughter are fully self-sufficient. They live in the same apartment, and Meisha can confidently pay her housing expenses without any support.','Meisha invested in her education','','publish','closed','open','','meisha-invested-in-her-education','','','2013-10-21 22:44:02','2013-10-21 22:44:02','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=431',34,'post','',0),(432,12,'2013-10-11 19:41:40','2013-10-11 19:41:40','','Meisha','','inherit','closed','open','','meisha','','','2013-10-11 19:41:40','2013-10-11 19:41:40','',431,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Meisha.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(435,12,'2013-10-11 20:55:34','2013-10-11 20:55:34','<h4><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-447\" alt=\"IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__105\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__105-1024x685.jpg\" width=\"600\" /></h4>\r\n<h4><span style=\"font-size: 1em;\">Sabrina shared her story at InnVision Shelter Network\'s Benefit Breakfast on October 10, 2013.</span></h4>\r\nGood morning. My name is Sabrina, I am 15 years old, and I am here to share my story.\r\n\r\nI was born at Peninsula Hospital right here in Burlingame. I’m currently a junior at Sequoia High School.\r\n\r\nGrowing up, it was just me and my mom. I know it sounds cheesy, but my mom is my best friend.\r\n\r\nI never lived with my dad. He wasn’t there for many significant moments of my life-- my first loose tooth, my first heart break. As I grew up, he missed out on watching me learn and grow. I called him, a few years ago, and he didn’t even recognize my voice. His absence affects me a lot, even though I try to forget him.\r\n\r\nI have always loved to write. I have filled notebooks with stories, poems, songs, and descriptions of the world around me. I have written a lot about my dad. I share my writing with my mom. She always believed in me—that I could be a writer, a journalist, anything I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nMy mom was a career waitress, and often worked long hours. When she was off the clock, however, we made the most of our time together. Money was often tight, but we always made it work.\r\n\r\nWhen I was a freshman in high school, my whole world was shaken up. My mom started having serious health problems, and was diagnosed with Parkinson’s disease. Recently, she was also diagnosed with breast cancer. I can’t explain how scary it is to think that I could lose the number one person in my life.\r\n\r\nHer health affected her ability to work. It became impossible for her to carry plates or spend all day on her feet in the restaurant, so she no longer had a job. We scraped by on her savings for a while, but eventually, it wasn’t enough.\r\n\r\nOne day, my mom picked me up from school; when I got in the car, the shakiness in her voice told me something wasn’t right, and I could see that she had been crying. She told me we got an eviction notice. My heart sank. This was one of those things that I never thought would happen to me.\r\n\r\nWe lost our home. I thought; that’s it? How is any of this fair? Nothing will ever feel like home again.\r\n\r\nI couldn’t stop crying. My mom held me and apologized; she thought she failed me as a mother. I told her: It’s not your fault. You didn’t choose this. We just hugged and cried. That was really all we could do.\r\n\r\nI was homeless my entire sophomore year of high school.\r\n\r\nAfter we lost our apartment, we floated between the homes of family and friends for a while. We stayed in a few cheap hotels, each time hoping that my mom would be able to find a job that she could do, despite her illness, and we would be able to return to normal life.\r\n\r\nThe instability really took a toll. I felt worn out each day, I began to feel hopeless. Everything was uncertain. When I was constantly moving and living out of suitcases, it became very difficult to decide what to focus on. Should school come first? Or my mom’s health? Or finding a place to stay that night?\r\n\r\nThen we came to InnVision Shelter Network. We started out in the emergency program at First Step, and then moved into the transitional program at Redwood Family House. I expected a giant room of cots, but this wasn’t the case. It didn’t even feel like a shelter. It was like moving into our very own apartment.\r\n\r\nAt Redwood, I met the Children’s Services Coordinator, Laura, who supported us every step of the way. I don’t think anyone could’ve helped us through it better. Laura and the other staff were always there for us, to help with anything we needed. They would bring stuff to our room because they knew that my mom had trouble getting out of bed after a surgery.\r\n\r\nWe were able to focus more on my mom’s health, and to start looking for housing. We were also waiting for a housing subsidy to come through because my mom was officially considered disabled. Since my mom was no longer able to write, I filled out the housing forms as we searched for places together. We worked as a team.\r\n\r\nIn my free time, I still loved writing. I’m part of my school newspaper, the Raven Report, as a staff reporter. This winter, I found out I was nominated for the National Young Leaders Conference in Washington, D.C.. I felt so proud and wanted to attend the conference. I told Laura about it, but I knew we couldn’t afford it, and didn’t expect to be able to go.\r\n\r\nLaura had different plans for me. She presented a portfolio of my writing to the Redwood Family House Support Committee. A few weeks later, she told me that a donor and supporter of InnVision Shelter Network had read my writing, and had offered to cover the cost of the trip. I never expected something like this would be possible. I had never even been on a plane before.\r\n\r\nLaura planned my flight, and helped get me ready for the trip. Everyone told me I would get lost in the airport, but I’m proud to say that I didn’t.\r\n\r\nThe conference was unlike anything I’ve experienced before. I met so many people who challenged my intelligence; I learned a lot about public speaking, and participated in a model congress. I made some amazing friends. None of this would have been possible without InnVision Shelter Network and one amazing donor.\r\n\r\nSoon after I returned from the conference, my mom and I finally found a house that would accept her housing subsidy— a cute 2 bedroom in Redwood City close to school. I have my own room. I have a place to come home to.\r\n\r\nWhile this past year has been the most challenging year of my life, I feel ready to get back on track. In my future, I definitely plan on attending college. My dream is to attend the Medill program at Northwestern University, and follow my passion to become a journalist.\r\n\r\nI was recently invited to attend the Global Young Leaders Conference, the next level up from the National Young Leaders Conference I attended this summer. Whether or not I am able to attend, it feels good to be recognized for my accomplishments, and I am happier now than I have felt for a long time.\r\n\r\nAt InnVision Shelter Network, I found people who believed in me, and I grew a lot. I will never forget Laura and the rest of the staff who helped me and my mom through this rough time.\r\n\r\nI know now that when I am older, I want to help others, like people helped me. Thank you for supporting InnVision Shelter Network—your support really makes a difference.\r\n\r\nI would like to close my speech by reading a poem I wrote. It’s called “Running.”\r\n\r\n<em>Running.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>From everyone who thinks you can’t succeed.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>From anything that brings you sadness or fear.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>From people you can never fully satisfy.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>From anything unhappy.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Running.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>To a place where you can be free.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>To a place where judgments aren’t made.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Towards comfort and joy.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>To anywhere but here.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Running.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>And I’ll never stop.</em>','Homeless in High School: Sabrina\'s Story','','publish','closed','open','','homeless-in-high-school-sabrinas-story','','','2013-10-21 22:42:03','2013-10-21 22:42:03','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=435',32,'post','',0),(438,2,'2013-10-11 22:07:54','2013-10-11 22:07:54',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','438','','','2014-07-08 15:22:01','2014-07-08 22:22:01','',9,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=438',25,'nav_menu_item','',0),(439,2,'2013-10-11 22:07:54','2013-10-11 22:07:54',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','439','','','2014-07-08 15:22:01','2014-07-08 22:22:01','',9,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=439',24,'nav_menu_item','',0),(440,2,'2013-10-11 22:07:54','2013-10-11 22:07:54',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','440','','','2014-07-08 15:22:01','2014-07-08 22:22:01','',9,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=440',23,'nav_menu_item','',0),(444,12,'2013-10-11 23:21:03','2013-10-11 23:21:03','<h4><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-445\" alt=\"IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__192\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__192.jpg\" width=\"600\" /></h4>\r\n<h4>Lynne Twist, global visionary and author of <i>The Soul of Money</i>, delivered the keynote address at InnVision Shelter Network’s Benefit Breakfast on October 10, 2013.</h4>\r\nLynne’s address about <i>The Power of Taking a Stand</i> highlighted the fact that while homelessness has become a global epidemic, it is still prevalent right here in Silicon Valley and on the San Francisco Peninsula. We don’t often connect poverty and homelessness with our community, because of the wealth we see around us. Lynne invited all of us to see the fact that homelessness exists in our community as a call to action.\r\n\r\nOne surprising fact Lynne shared was that storage is one of the fastest growing industries in the United States. As a society, we devote energy and resources to building homes not for those in the community who need them most, but to house our excess material possessions. She encouraged the audience to consider how we allocate the resources that we have, and to think about giving those resources to our neighbors most in need.\r\n\r\nDuring her storied career, Lynne has traveled the globe working to address the root causes of poverty. She spoke about how simply providing food is not enough—we have to change the way we think about people living in poverty. When we stop thinking of people as “the poor” and start treating them like whole and complete people, we are better equipped to offer the compassion and resources they need to get back on their feet.\r\n\r\nRather than simply providing food or a place to sleep, InnVision Shelter Network treats our clients as whole people with dignity and respect. We connect our clients to lasting resources so that they can return to self-sufficiency.\r\n\r\nThank you, Lynne, for your inspirational speech and your commitment to ending poverty.','Benefit Breakfast: Lynne Twist Keynote Speech','','publish','closed','open','','benefit-breakfast-lynne-twist-keynote-speech','','','2013-10-16 17:10:52','2013-10-16 17:10:52','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=444',33,'post','',0),(445,12,'2013-10-11 23:20:06','2013-10-11 23:20:06','','IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__192','','inherit','closed','open','','ivsn_benefitbreakfast__192','','','2013-10-11 23:20:06','2013-10-11 23:20:06','',444,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__192.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(447,12,'2013-10-11 23:26:24','2013-10-11 23:26:24','','IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__105','','inherit','closed','open','','ivsn_benefitbreakfast__105','','','2013-10-11 23:26:24','2013-10-11 23:26:24','',435,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/IVSN_BenefitBreakfast__105.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(451,2,'2013-10-14 23:25:06','2013-10-14 23:25:06','','donate_button_purple','','inherit','closed','open','','donate_button_purple','','','2013-10-14 23:25:06','2013-10-14 23:25:06','',43,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/donate_button_purple.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(452,2,'2013-10-14 23:25:08','2013-10-14 23:25:08','','donate_button','','inherit','closed','open','','donate_button','','','2013-10-14 23:25:08','2013-10-14 23:25:08','',43,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/donate_button.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(453,2,'2013-10-14 23:25:09','2013-10-14 23:25:09','','volunteer_button','','inherit','closed','open','','volunteer_button','','','2013-10-14 23:25:09','2013-10-14 23:25:09','',43,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/volunteer_button.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(457,12,'2013-10-15 16:25:17','2013-10-15 16:25:17','','Print - copie','','inherit','closed','open','','print-copie','','','2013-10-15 16:25:17',