</a>','Publications2','','draft','closed','open','','','','','2014-03-07 11:15:03','2014-03-07 19:15:03','',6,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=732',76,'page','',0),(733,12,'2014-03-07 13:03:59','2014-03-07 21:03:59','','IVSN Annual Report 2013_donorlist','','inherit','closed','open','','ivsn-annual-report-2013_donorlist','','','2014-03-07 13:03:59','2014-03-07 21:03:59','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/IVSN-Annual-Report-2013_donorlist.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(734,12,'2014-03-07 13:47:59','2014-03-07 21:47:59','','Annual Report 030714_web','','inherit','closed','open','','annual-report-030714_web','','','2014-03-07 13:47:59','2014-03-07 21:47:59','',250,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Annual-Report-030714_web.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(738,12,'2014-03-11 10:29:25','2014-03-11 17:29:25','<h1>Meal Provider Volunteer Manual</h1>\r\nThank you for volunteering to provide a meal for the InnVision Shelter Network clients!\r\n\r\nPlease read through the links below for detailed instructions on meal service volunteering.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Meal-Provider-Volunteer-Manual-9-2-14.pdf\">Download the Meal Provider Volunteer Manual in PDF format</a>\r\n<h2>Site-Specific Guidelines</h2>\r\nPlease read the guidelines for the site where you will volunteer, such as kitchen functionality, age restrictions and more.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/meal-provider-volunteer-manual/meal-provider-manual-commercial-street-inn/\">Commercial Street Inn, San Jose</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/meal-provider-volunteer-manual/meal-provider-manual-first-step-for-families/\">First Step for Families, San Mateo</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/meal-provider-volunteer-manual/meal-provider-manual-julian-street-inn/\">Julian Street Inn, San Jose</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/meal-provider-volunteer-manual/meal-provider-manual-maple-street-shelter/\">Maple Street Shelter, Redwood City</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/meal-provider-volunteer-manual/meal-provider-manual-montgomery-street-inn/\">Montgomery Street Inn, San Jose</a></li>\r\n	<li>Other facilities please contact <span style=\"color: #1a1a1a;\">Nathan Porras at </span><a style=\"color: #0066cc;\" href=\"mailto:nporras@ivsn.org\">nporras@ivsn.org </a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Food Health and Safety</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/food-health-and-safety/\">Read instructions on food health and safety.</a>\r\n<h2>Suggested Menus</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/suggested-menus/\">View suggested menus for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.</a>','Meal Provider Volunteer Manual','','publish','closed','open','','meal-provider-volunteer-manual','','','2014-09-02 11:54:10','2014-09-02 18:54:10','',188,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=738',34,'page','',0),(739,12,'2014-03-11 10:38:29','2014-03-11 17:38:29','<h1>Meal Provider Manual: Commercial Street Inn</h1>\r\n<img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-148\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/ivsn_homeless_shelter_commercial_street_inn-320x214.jpg\" alt=\"ivsn_homeless_shelter_commercial_street_inn\" width=\"320\" height=\"214\" />\r\n<h2>Location</h2>\r\nCommercial Street Inn\r\n260 Commercial Street, San Jose, CA 95112 (<a href=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Commercial+Street+Inn+260+Commercial+Street,+San+Jose,+CA+95112&amp;hl=en&amp;ll=37.359959,-121.900027&amp;spn=0.012007,0.010579&amp;sll=37.359959,-121.900027&amp;sspn=0.012007,0.010579&amp;gl=us&amp;hq=Commercial+Street+Inn&amp;hnear=260+Commercial+St,+San+Jose,+California+95112&amp;t=m&amp;z=16\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\r\nInterim housing for 55 women and children\r\n<h2>Recommended Group Size</h2>\r\n8 to 10 participants\r\n<h2>Age Requirement for Volunteers</h2>\r\nAll ages (must be 12+ to work in the kitchen)\r\n<h2 style=\"color: #000000;\">Meal Service Only</h2>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">An opportunity to serve meals provided by our partner agencies and organizations</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">• Lunch: Monday - Friday\r\n• Dinner: Monday – Thursday</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 style=\"color: #000000;\">\r\nMeal Preparation &amp; Service</h2>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Groups are asked to provide and serve meals</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">• Breakfast: 7 days per week\r\n• Lunch: Saturday, Sunday\r\n• Dinner: Friday, Saturday, Sunday</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>What time are meals served?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breakfast – Served at 7am</li>\r\n	<li>Lunch – Served at Noon</li>\r\n	<li>Dinner – Served at 6pm</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>How many residents will attend?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breakfast\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekdays: 16-20</li>\r\n	<li>Weekend: 20-26</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Lunch\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekends only - 8-12</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Dinner\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekdays – 25-35</li>\r\n	<li>Weekends – 18-22</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Can we Cook and Serve a Meal Onsite? Is there a kitchen available?</h2>\r\nYes! There is a kitchen enough for 5 people to cook in comfortably.\r\n<h2>What is the kitchen equipped with?</h2>\r\nCommercial St. Inn has a commercial kitchen equipment with a gas cook top, convection ovens, a freezer, and a refrigerator.\r\n\r\n3 Food Warmers/serving stations an ice machine, and enough cafeteria style plates, bowls, and eating utensils to serve the residents.\r\n<h2>Can we cook the meal elsewhere and drop it off?</h2>\r\nYes! While we would love to have you stay and engage with the residents over a meal that you provide, we understand that your schedules are busy.\r\n\r\nPlease make a special note that you will ONLY be dropping off a meal in your sign up form\r\n<h2>Will all of the food I bring be eaten if there are leftovers?</h2>\r\nYes, leftovers will be stored and served to residents who are unable to join the meal due to a schedule conflict.\r\n<h2>Can we perform religious services during the meal?</h2>\r\nNo, InnVision Shelter Network receives federal funding which mandates nonsectarian activities .\r\n<h2>What type of food should we provide?</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/suggested-menus/\">View suggested menus for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.</a> Get creative and have fun with this. We do want the meal to be as nutritious and as well rounded as possible.\r\n<h2>Do we need to clean up after the meal?</h2>\r\nYes, we ask that our volunteer groups clean up following the meal .','Meal Provider Manual: Commercial Street Inn','','publish','closed','open','','meal-provider-manual-commercial-street-inn','','','2014-09-02 11:58:38','2014-09-02 18:58:38','',738,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=739',33,'page','',0),(740,12,'2014-03-11 10:45:41','2014-03-11 17:45:41','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-160\" alt=\"ivsn_homeless_shelter_first_step_for_families\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/ivsn_homeless_shelter_first_step_for_families-320x240.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" />Meal Provider Manual: First Step for Families</h1>\r\n<h2>Location</h2>\r\nFirst Step for Families\r\n325 Villa Terrace, San Mateo, CA 94401 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/ovGDS\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\r\nStabilization and interim housing for 39 families\r\n<h2>Meal Sign-up Calendar</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://volunteer.ivsn.org/IVSNCalendar.aspx?LocID=51\">View the calendar and sign up to provide a meal</a>\r\n<h2>Recommended  Volunteer Group Size</h2>\r\n5 to 15 participants\r\n<h2>Age Requirement for Volunteers</h2>\r\nAll ages (must be 12+ to work in the kitchen)\r\n<h2>Meal Service Opportunities</h2>\r\nDinner – 7 days per week\r\n<h2>What time are meals served?</h2>\r\nDinner Weekdays: 5 pm (food out 5-8pm)\r\nDinner Weekend: 6pm\r\n<h2>How many residents will attend?</h2>\r\nWeekdays: 60-75\r\nWeekend: 40-50\r\n<h2>Is there a kitchen?</h2>\r\nThere are three residential size kitchens on site, which the residents use. These kitchens are appropriate for warming and serving food, but they are NOT appropriate for prepping and cooking an entire meal.\r\n<h2>Can we cook the meal elsewhere and drop it off?</h2>\r\nYes! While we would love to have you stay and engage with the residents over a meal that you provide, we understand that your schedules are busy.\r\n\r\nPlease make a special note on your sign up form if you will ONLY be dropping off a meal.\r\n<h2>Will all of the food I bring be eaten even if there are leftovers?</h2>\r\nYes, leftovers will be stored and served to those residents who are unable to join the meal due to a schedule conflict.\r\n<h2>Can we perform religious services during the meal?</h2>\r\nNo, InnVision Shelter Network receives federal funding which mandates nonsectarian activities .\r\n<h2>What type of food should we provide?</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/suggested-menus/\">View suggested menus for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.</a> Get creative and have fun with this. We do want the meal to be as nutritious and as well rounded as possible.\r\n<h2>Do we need to clean up after the meal?</h2>\r\nYes, we ask that our volunteer groups clean up following the meal .','Meal Provider Manual: First Step for Families','','publish','closed','open','','meal-provider-manual-first-step-for-families','','','2014-03-20 10:04:55','2014-03-20 17:04:55','',738,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=740',27,'page','',0),(743,12,'2014-03-11 11:06:43','2014-03-11 18:06:43','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-153\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/ivsn_homeless_shelter_julian_street_inn-320x214.jpg\" alt=\"ivsn_homeless_shelter_julian_street_inn\" width=\"320\" height=\"214\" />Meal Provider Manual: Julian Street Inn</h1>\r\n<h2>Location</h2>\r\nJulian Street Inn\r\n546 W Julian Street, San Jose, CA 95110 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/JBxgq\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\r\nStabilization and interim housing for 70 single adults diagnosed with mental illness\r\n<h2>Recommended Group Size</h2>\r\n8 to 15 participants\r\n<h2>Age Requirement for Volunteers</h2>\r\n18+ - No volunteers under the age of 18 at this location. This is a shelter for single adults.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-weight: 300; color: #000000;\">Meal Service Only</h2>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">An opportunity to serve meals provided by our partner agencies and organizations</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">• Lunch: Monday – Friday\r\n• Dinner: Monday – Thursday</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 style=\"font-weight: 300; color: #000000;\">Meal Preparation &amp; Service</h2>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Groups are asked to provide and serve meals</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">• Breakfast: 7 days per week\r\n• Lunch: Saturday, Sunday\r\n• Dinner: Friday, Saturday, Sunday</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>What time are meals served?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breakfast Weekdays: served at 6am</li>\r\n	<li>Breakfast Weekends: served at 7:30am</li>\r\n	<li>Lunch: 12:30-1pm</li>\r\n	<li>Dinner: 6pm-7pm</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>How many residents will attend?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breakfast\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekdays – 30</li>\r\n	<li>Weekend – 35</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Lunch\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekdays – 35</li>\r\n	<li>Weekends - 35</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Dinner\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekdays – 50</li>\r\n	<li>Weekends – 50</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Can we Cook and Serve a Meal Onsite? Is there a kitchen available?</h2>\r\nYes! Julian Street Inn has a kitchen which can accommodate a maximum of 6 people cooking.\r\n<h2>What is the kitchen equipped with?</h2>\r\nJulian Street Inn has a commercial kitchen that is equipped with two gas cook tops, two convection ovens, a freezer and a refrigerator.\r\n\r\n3 Food warmers/serving station, ice machine and enough cafeteria style plates, bowls, and eating utensils to serve all the residents.\r\n\r\nThere are no knives available.\r\n<h2>Can we cook the meal elsewhere and drop it off?</h2>\r\nYes! While we would love to have you stay and engage with the residents over a meal that you provide, we understand that your schedules are busy.\r\n\r\nPlease make a special note that you will ONLY be dropping off a meal in your sign up form\r\n<h2>Will all of the food I bring be eaten if there are leftovers?</h2>\r\nYes, leftovers will be stored and served to residents who are unable to join the meal due to a schedule conflict.\r\n<h2>Can we perform religious services during the meal?</h2>\r\nNo, InnVision Shelter Network receives federal funding which mandates nonsectarian activities .\r\n<h2>What type of food should we provide?</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/suggested-menus/\">View suggested menus for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.</a> Get creative and have fun with this. We do want the meal to be as nutritious and as well rounded as possible.\r\n<h2>Do we need to clean up after the meal?</h2>\r\nYes, we ask that our volunteer groups clean up following the meal .','Meal Provider Manual: Julian Street Inn','','publish','closed','open','','meal-provider-manual-julian-street-inn','','','2014-09-02 11:59:28','2014-09-02 18:59:28','',738,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=743',32,'page','',0),(744,12,'2014-03-11 11:10:41','2014-03-11 18:10:41','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-161\" alt=\"ivsn_homeless_shelter_maple_street\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/ivsn_homeless_shelter_maple_street-320x239.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"239\" />Meal Provider Manual: Maple Street Shelter</h1>\r\n<h2>Location</h2>\r\n1580A Maple Street\r\nRedwood City, CA 94063 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/5YkS5\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\r\nStabilization and interim housing for 75 single men and women\r\n<h2>Recommended Group Size</h2>\r\n10 to 20 participants\r\n<h2>Age Requirement for Volunteers</h2>\r\nAdults and youth are eligible to volunteer. Ages 12+ must have adult supervision and be within sight of the adult at all time.\r\n<h2>Meal Service Opportunities</h2>\r\nBreakfast – 7 days per week\r\nLunch – Saturday and Sunday Only\r\nDinner – 7 days per week\r\n<h2>What time are meals served?</h2>\r\nBreakfast – Served between 6am- 9am\r\nLunch - Noon\r\nDinner – 5pm\r\n<h2>How many residents will attend?</h2>\r\nBreakfast: 55-75 people\r\nLunch: 20-30 people\r\nDinner: 55-75 people\r\n<h2>Is there a kitchen available?</h2>\r\nNo – there is no kitchen available.  There is one full size warmer that is capable of keeping food warm, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">NOT</span> heating it up.\r\n<h2>Can we cook the meal elsewhere and drop it off?</h2>\r\nYes! While we would love to have you stay and engage with the residents over a meal that you provide, we understand that your schedules are busy.\r\n\r\nPlease make a special note that you will ONLY be dropping off a meal in your sign up form\r\n<h2>Will all of the food I bring be eaten if there are leftovers?</h2>\r\nYes, leftovers will be stored and served to residents who are unable to join the meal due to a schedule conflict.\r\n<h2>Can we perform religious services during the meal?</h2>\r\nNo, InnVision Shelter Network receives federal funding which mandates nonsectarian activities .\r\n<h2>What type of food should we provide?</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/suggested-menus/\">View suggested menus for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.</a> Get creative and have fun with this. We do want the meal to be as nutritious and as well rounded as possible.\r\n<h2>Do we need to clean up after the meal?</h2>\r\nYes, we ask that our volunteer groups clean up following the meal .','Meal Provider Manual: Maple Street Shelter','','publish','closed','open','','meal-provider-manual-maple-street-shelter','','','2014-03-20 10:04:50','2014-03-20 17:04:50','',738,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=744',31,'page','',0),(745,12,'2014-03-11 11:14:31','2014-03-11 18:14:31','<h1>Meal Provider Manual: Montgomery Street Inn</h1>\r\n<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-162\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/ivsn_homeless_shelter_montgomery_street_inn-320x214.jpg\" alt=\"ivsn_homeless_shelter_montgomery_street_inn\" width=\"320\" height=\"214\" /></h1>\r\n<h2>Location</h2>\r\n358 N Montgomery Street\r\nSan Jose, CA 95110 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/rTDfn\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\r\nStabilization housing for 46 single men and interim housing for 39 single men\r\n<h2>Recommended Group Size</h2>\r\n8 to 15 participants\r\n<h2>Age Requirement for Volunteers</h2>\r\nNo volunteers under 18 years of age. This is a shelter for single adults.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-weight: 300; color: #000000;\">Meal Service Only</h2>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">An opportunity to serve meals provided by our partner agencies and organizations</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">• Lunch: Monday – Friday\r\n• Dinner: Monday – Thursday</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 style=\"font-weight: 300; color: #000000;\">Meal Preparation &amp; Service</h2>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Groups are asked to provide and serve meals</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">• Breakfast: 7 days per week\r\n• Lunch: Saturday, Sunday\r\n• Dinner: Friday, Saturday, Sunday</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>What time are meals served?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breakfast – Served from 6am-7am</li>\r\n	<li>Lunch – Served from 12pm-1pm</li>\r\n	<li>Dinner – Served from 6pm-7pm</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>How many residents will attend?</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breakfast\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekdays – 50 people</li>\r\n	<li>Weekends – 60 people</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Lunch – 30 people</li>\r\n	<li>Dinner\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Weekdays – 70 people</li>\r\n	<li>Weekends – 70 people</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Can we prepare our meal on site?</h2>\r\nThere is a fully operational kitchen available for meal partners to prepare a meal that can accommodate 8 people cooking.\r\n<h2>What is the kitchen equipped with?</h2>\r\nReusable plates, cups, and utensils. There are also cooking pots, pans, knives, and serving spoons for volunteers to use when cooking on site.\r\n<h2>Can we cook the meal elsewhere and drop it off?</h2>\r\nYes! While we would love to have you stay and engage with the residents over a meal that you provide, we understand that your schedules are busy.\r\n\r\nPlease make a special note that you will ONLY be dropping off a meal in your sign up form\r\n<h2>Will all of the food I bring be eaten if there are leftovers?</h2>\r\nYes, leftovers will be stored and served to residents who are unable to join the meal due to a schedule conflict.\r\n<h2>Can we perform religious services during the meal?</h2>\r\nNo, InnVision Shelter Network receives federal funding which mandates nonsectarian activities .\r\n<h2>What type of food should we provide?</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/suggested-menus/\">View suggested menus for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.</a> Get creative and have fun with this. We do want the meal to be as nutritious and as well rounded as possible.\r\n<h2>Do we need to clean up after the meal?</h2>\r\nYes, we ask that our volunteer groups clean up following the meal .','Meal Provider Manual: Montgomery Street Inn','','publish','closed','open','','meal-provider-manual-montgomery-street-inn','','','2014-09-02 12:00:09','2014-09-02 19:00:09','',738,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=745',30,'page','',0),(746,12,'2014-03-11 11:17:49','2014-03-11 18:17:49','<h1>Food Health and Safety</h1>\r\n<h2>Allergies</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Some clients may have religious restrictions from certain foods and may politely refuse certain types of food.</li>\r\n	<li>Please omit peanuts, sprouts, and spicy ingredients from dishes.</li>\r\n	<li>Clearly mark ingredients on a card or a piece of paper and place it in front of dishes before serving food.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Preparation</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>We request that any volunteer that is ill refrain from contact with food preparation and food service.</li>\r\n	<li>Before food preparation, it is important to clean and sanitize preparation tools such as knives, cutting boards, utensils, bowls, etc. to avoid possible cross contamination.</li>\r\n	<li>Use separate utensils such as knives, spoons, and cutting boards for each food.</li>\r\n	<li>Wear food handling gloves and wash hands immediately after contact with different food types, touching face, and/ or after restroom use.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Hot Food</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Food must be cooked to the recommended safe temperature, whole raw beef, pork, fish and eggs must be cooked internally to 145 º and temperature held for 15 seconds.</li>\r\n	<li>Food must be cooked to the recommended safe temperature, raw ground meat and fish must be cooked internally to 155º and temperature held for 15 seconds.</li>\r\n	<li>Food must be cooked to the recommended safe temperature, raw or ground poultry must be cooked internally to 165º and temperature held for 15 seconds.<b> </b></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Things to Bring</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b> </b>Paper plates for serving dinner and dessert (if also brought)</li>\r\n	<li> Plastic or biodegradable cutlery</li>\r\n	<li> Tin foil</li>\r\n	<li> Extra serving utensils</li>\r\n	<li> Large bowls &amp; serving/salad tongs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Safe Transportation of Food</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Food must be transported separately from chemicals and other non-food items. (Food must be covered and free of contaminants, i.e. leaking liquids into other dishes)</li>\r\n	<li>Hot food in transportation must either be stored in heat controlled temperature boxes, or must be transported to the service site within 45 minutes after being cooked. (Food may be reheated to an internal temperature of not less than 140º at service time.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Safe Food Service</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Please do not wear loose fitting jewelry or clothing that may fall or drop into food.</li>\r\n	<li>Volunteers must wash hands, waterproof and bandage cuts and use food service gloves.</li>\r\n	<li>Be cautious of hot dishes, surfaces and utensils</li>\r\n	<li>Wipe down spills and clean as you go using food safe cleaners and sanitizers provided by InnVision Shelter Network.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Clean Up</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Clean up is also required from your group. Please use the food-safe cleaning and sanitizing products provided by InnVision Shelter Network to clean surfaces used</li>\r\n	<li>Clear and clean all pans, trays and utensils that belong to the facility, and return them to the storage location they came from</li>\r\n	<li>Remove and dispose of all garbage generated</li>\r\n	<li>Safely cover leftover items and place in refrigerator(s)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>If you have any questions, there is always a staff person onsite who will be happy to assist you.</b>','Food Health and Safety','','publish','closed','open','','food-health-and-safety','','','2014-03-11 11:17:49','2014-03-11 18:17:49','',188,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=746',29,'page','',0),(747,12,'2014-03-11 11:24:26','2014-03-11 18:24:26','<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\">Suggested Menus</h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"#Breakfast\">Breakfast Menu Ideas</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"#Lunch\">Lunch Menu Ideas</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"#Dinner\">Dinner Menu Ideas</a></p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h2 id=\"Breakfast\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Breakfast Menu Ideas</h2>\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><strong>Breakfast Burritos – Serves 50</strong></h5>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">50 Large eggs\r\n10 Ounces OR 2 Cups frozen corn\r\n3/4 Cup low fat milk\r\n3 Pounds, 2 Ounces TURKEY HAM diced into 1/2-inch pieces\r\n12 Ounces fresh green peppers diced\r\n14 Ounces onions diced\r\n1 fresh tomatoes diced\r\n1/4 Cup prepared mustard\r\n2 Teaspoons granulated garlic\r\n1 Tablespoon hot pepper sauce\r\n2 Teaspoons salt\r\n50 at least 1.1 ounces flour tortillas\r\n3 Pounds, 2 Ounces mild salsa</p>\r\n\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><strong>California Eggs &amp; Sausage Casserole - 80-100 people</strong></h5>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">60 Large eggs\r\n10 cups milk\r\n15 cups biscuit mix\r\n5 lb. Sausage (cooked and crumbled)\r\n20 cups grated cheddar cheese</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Preheat oven to 350 degrees.  In a large bowl, break eggs and add milk. Blend well.\r\nAdd remaining ingredients, mix and pour into a greased pan.\r\nBake about 40 minutes (or until eggs are set). Submitted by Cathy Smith</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">No serving amount with this, guestimate 80-100 serving.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>For more great Breakfast ideas please visit: </b><strong><a href=\"http://www.yummly.com/recipes/breakfast-for-a-crowd\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.yummly.com/recipes/breakfast-for-a-crowd</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h2 id=\"Lunch\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Lunch Menu Ideas</h2>\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><strong>Sloppy Joes – 16 people</strong></h5>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">4lbs of ground beef\r\n2 medium onions, Chopped\r\n16 hamburger buns, or 48 party-size potato rolls\r\n1/2 lb, 13 oz. jar of pasta sauce\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">1/4 cup firmly packed brown sugar (optional)</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Brown ground beef with onions in 7-quart saucepot; drain.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Stir in Pasta Sauce and brown sugar. Bring to a boil over high heat. Reduce heat to medium and simmer covered, stirring occasionally, 10 minutes. Serve on buns.</p>\r\n\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><strong>Taco Salad – 35 people</strong></h5>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">31/2 lbs lean ground beef\r\n41/3 ozs taco seasoning mix\r\n31/2 cups cheddar cheese (grated)\r\n13/4 red onion (chopped)\r\n13/4 yellow onion (chopped)\r\n31/2 heads iceberg lettuce (chopped)\r\n7 tomatoes (chopped i use roma)\r\n31/2 avocados (peeled and chopped)\r\n22/3 cups black olives (sliced)\r\n21 cups nacho chip\r\n14 ozs catalina dressing (french salad, work)</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: left;\">\r\n	<li>Brown ground beef with the chopped yellow onion (not red).</li>\r\n	<li>Add in only 1 package taco mix (and water according to the package direction); set aside to cool completely.</li>\r\n	<li>In a large bowl, mix together chopped lettuce, tomatoes, cheddar cheese (can use more than 2 cups if desired, and the cheese may be cubed small instead of shredded) avocados, red onion, olives, and the second package of taco seasoning mix.</li>\r\n	<li>Add to cooled beef mixture; toss to combine.</li>\r\n	<li>Just before serving toss with the salad dressing.</li>\r\n	<li>The last step (JUST BEFORE SERVING) is to mix in about three-quarters of the package of crushed Doritos, leaving the rest on the side for your guests who want extra (they will get soggy if you mix them in too early!).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>For more great lunch ideas please visit: </b><a href=\"http://www.yummly.com/recipes/lunch-for-a-crowd\" target=\"_blank\"><b>http://www.yummly.com/recipes/lunch-for-a-crowd</b></a></p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h2 id=\"Dinner\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Dinner Menu Ideas</h2>\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><strong>Chicken Tetrazzini – 60 people</strong></h5>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">3 lbs spaghetti (broken into pieces)\r\n963/4 ozs condensed cream of mushroom soup\r\n36 ozs shredded cheddar cheese\r\n18 cups chicken breast (shredded boiled, meat)\r\n3 lbs mushrooms (sauteed)\r\n12 ozs peppers (sliced pimento, drained)\r\n6 cups chicken broth (reserved)</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Preheat oven to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C). Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add uncooked spaghetti (broken into thirds) to the pot and cook for 8 to 10 minutes or until al dente. Drain and set aside.<b></b></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">In a large saucepan, heat soup over low heat. Add shredded cheese (reserve some for topping) and stir together. Then add the cooked shredded chicken, mushrooms, pimento peppers and cooked spaghetti and stir all together. Add enough of the reserved broth to make it \'sloppy\' and mix all together.<b></b></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Pour mixture into a 9x13 inch baking dish. Sprinkle reserved shredded cheese on top and bake in the preheated oven for 25 to 35 minutes or until bubbly.</p>\r\n\r\n<h5 style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\"><b>Complete Spaghetti Dinner - Serves 50-60 people – Approximate Cost   $200</b></h5>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">(Ingredients priced at Safeway, using the club card)</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Spaghetti:\r\n10 pounds spaghetti\r\n10 jars spaghetti sauce\r\n5 pounds hamburger (optional)\r\n3 bottles parmesan cheese</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><b>For more great dinner ideas please visit: </b><a href=\"http://www.yummly.com/recipes/dinner-for-a-crowd\" target=\"_blank\"><b>http://www.yummly.com/recipes/dinner-for-a-crowd</b></a></p>','Suggested Menus','','publish','closed','open','','suggested-menus','','','2014-03-11 11:29:37','2014-03-11 18:29:37','',188,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=747',28,'page','',0),(750,12,'2014-03-11 11:36:07','2014-03-11 18:36:07',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','750','','','2014-08-26 14:46:58','2014-08-26 21:46:58','',188,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=750',9,'nav_menu_item','',0),(751,12,'2014-03-11 11:36:07','2014-03-11 18:36:07',' ','','','publish','closed','open','','751','','','2014-08-26 14:46:58','2014-08-26 21:46:58','',188,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=751',8,'nav_menu_item','',0),(752,12,'2014-03-11 11:36:07','2014-03-11 18:36:07','','Meal Provider Manual','','publish','closed','open','','meal-provider-manual','','','2014-08-26 14:46:58','2014-08-26 21:46:58','',188,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=752',7,'nav_menu_item','',0),(753,12,'2014-03-11 13:46:39','2014-03-11 20:46:39','','March Benefit Parking Map','','inherit','closed','open','','march-benefit-parking-map','','','2014-03-11 13:46:39','2014-03-11 20:46:39','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/March-Benefit-Parking-Map.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(754,12,'2014-03-14 11:45:26','2014-03-14 18:45:26','<em>Katie Palacio shared her story at InnVision Shelter Network\'s Community Update &amp; Benefit Breakfast on March 13, 2014 in San Jose.</em>\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/nBDwxFZqW3Y?list=PLGs-sSlZPR7OuzfDjYPbyFz35kjU7tSRM\" height=\"315\" width=\"560\" allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe>\r\n<h2><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">My name is Katie Palacio.</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">I have three children: my 16-year-old daughter Sophia, 9-year-old Georgia, and my youngest Jacob, is seven. </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">In the past I have been a business owner, and a stay-at-home mother.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">In my more recent past I was a client at the Villa, an interim housing program for women and children run by InnVision Shelter Network.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">I was raised in an upper middle class family in Willow Glen, Naglee Park, and the Rose Garden. </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">My mother and stepfather were very successful business people who were also active philanthropists.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Each Thanksgiving, after the table had been cleared and the dishes washed, our blended family of 11 (yes…11!) would sit down for a meeting to decide which charities would be the beneficiaries of our family foundation. </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Each of my brothers and sisters and I were allotted $1,000 to give to the charity of our choice.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">I was proud to come from a family that was aware of those who had less than us, and willing to help. </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">However, while I was aware of poverty, I was never really face-to-face with it save for the drive-through donation station at Sacred Heart.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">I married well, as my mother would say, and started to recreate the life that I had as a child. </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">We had a house in Los Gatos Hills, our children attended high performing schools, and we vacationed in the Bahamas.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">My life looked great on the outside. </span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">But as we all know, appearances can be deceiving.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">My marriage became increasingly abusive, and it wasn’t long before I was estranged from my family, forced to give up ownership of my half of the equity in our home, and taken off bank accounts so I had no access to money.</span>\r\n\r\nThe emotional and physical abuse from my husband, combined with the death of my mother after a long bout with cancer, left me with a depression so debilitating that often I could not get out of bed. I was ashamed and embarrassed at what my life had come to. In 2011, after 10 years of marriage, I finally had enough.\r\n<h2>I took the biggest leap of faith that I had ever taken in my life and called a domestic violence shelter.</h2>\r\nThat night, as I lay in the bottom bunk sleeping under a stranger, I was scared for what the future would bring. I had thirty days at the shelter to figure out my next move. I had no source of income. I hadn’t worked for 7 years. Truth be told, I was at the lowest point of my life.\r\n\r\nWhile Sophia thankfully had a place to live with her father and stepmother, I was still responsible for my two little ones. What was I going to do? I was terrified. How was I going to feed my children? I needed help.  I needed to ask for it.\r\n\r\nThe case workers at the shelter gave me a list of places that could help me, and InnVision Shelter Network was on that list.\r\n\r\nI received a referral for the Villa, and talked to Rick, the case manager there, who was gracious and respectful.\r\n\r\nWith his help, Georgia and Jake and I moved into the Villa on January 17<sup>th</sup>, 2012.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Initially, I kept to myself.  I am not proud to say this, but I didn’t think I had anything in common with my fellow women at the Villa.</span>\r\n\r\nI’d arrived at the Villa in a Lexus, with a Burberry scarf around my neck. Some of the other ladies were not shy about giving me the side eye, and I couldn’t blame them. In fact, I later wrote a funny creative writing piece called: “Don<a href=\"http://iamaredheadedstepchild.blogspot.com/2012/04/dont-show-up-to-homeless-shelter.html\" target=\"_blank\">’t show up to the homeless shelter wearing a Burberry scarf, no seriously, it’s not a good idea</a>.”\r\n\r\nAgain, appearances can be deceiving. Because the Burberry scarf was my mother’s that I wore for sentimental reasons. The Lexus was not in my name, had not been registered for 6 months, and every time I saw a police officer behind me I was convinced I was going to jail from my expired tags.\r\n\r\nIt was through my children that I realized that the other women and I at the Villa had more similarities than differences. When I cooked dinner in the community kitchen, Georgia and Jake started playing with the other kids. While they played, I started to talk to the mothers.\r\n\r\nI learned that we had all experienced great levels of trauma and PTSD in our lives.  Most of us had experienced violence. Sexual assault. Abuse. Sometimes struggles with addiction.\r\n\r\nAll of us loved our children. All of us had hopes and dreams, hobbies, senses of humor, favorite books and TV shows.\r\n\r\nI found community and discovered a commonality in women that I previously thought I had nothing in common with. I was able to see…to <i>really</i> see…how poverty affects women and children.\r\n<h2>My experience at the Villa was the reason I chose to go back to school.</h2>\r\nI wanted to help myself. And I wanted to help my sisters in poverty. I saw that <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">my</span> story is <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">her</span> story is <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">our</span> story.\r\n\r\nI applied to both UC Santa Cruz and Cal-Berkeley. I’m shocked and delighted to say that I got into both schools. I am thoroughly convinced that I got in because of my essay about my time at the Villa, and how it had changed my world view and shaped my path in life.\r\n\r\nUCSC offered me a full ride and grants to pay my rent in Family Student Housing, so I decided to accept their offer. I am now in my first year at UCSC, double majoring in Feminist Studies and Politics, with every intention to go to graduate school for Public Policy.\r\n\r\nIn reflecting upon my experience at the Villa, the reason that I was able to do what I did was not because I was an individual pulling myself up by my bootstraps.\r\n\r\nIt was because of Rick, the case manager.\r\n\r\nIt was because of Debra Chavez, the site director, whom I consider a mentor more than she knows.\r\n\r\nIt was because of you, and you, and you, who generously donate money and time to InnVision Shelter Network.\r\n\r\nThank you. I could not have done it without you.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">We</span> could not do it without you.\r\n\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','My Story is Her Story is Our Story','','publish','closed','open','','my-story-is-her-story-is-our-story','','','2014-03-17 11:53:56','2014-03-17 18:53:56','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=754',22,'post','',0),(755,12,'2014-03-14 11:41:32','2014-03-14 18:41:32','','katie palacio thumbnail','','inherit','closed','open','','katie-palacio-thumbnail','','','2014-03-14 11:41:32','2014-03-14 18:41:32','',754,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/katie-palacio-thumbnail.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(756,12,'2014-03-14 11:44:38','2014-03-14 18:44:38','','katie palacio','','inherit','closed','open','','katie-palacio','','','2014-03-14 11:44:38','2014-03-14 18:44:38','',754,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/katie-palacio.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(760,12,'2014-03-18 11:58:56','2014-03-18 18:58:56','','web image_volunteer appreciation','','inherit','closed','open','','web-image_volunteer-appreciation','','','2014-03-18 11:58:56','2014-03-18 18:58:56','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/web-image_volunteer-appreciation.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(769,12,'2014-03-21 10:43:08','2014-03-21 17:43:08','<h1>Accounts Payable Specialist</h1>\r\nInnVision Shelter Network (IVSN) is the leading provider of shelter/housing and supportive services across Silicon Valley and the San Francisco Peninsula.  IVSN operates 18 sites from San Jose to Daly City, providing stabilization, interim, and permanent supportive housing for homeless families and individuals as they return to permanent housing and self-sufficiency. IVSN helps over 20,000 homeless people annually through collaborative partnerships and a broad range of supportive services provided by ~250 dedicated staff members.\r\n\r\nWe are seeking an experienced Accounts Payable (AP) Specialist to own the AP process from invoices to disbursement.  This role is based in our Menlo Park administration office.\r\n\r\n<b><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">PRIMARY DUTIES</span></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b>Full Cycle AP </b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Properly code, enter, reconcile, and process approximately 250 payments per week, including vendor invoices and employee expense and mileage reimbursements.</li>\r\n	<li>Understand and interpret vendor invoices, statements, and other requests for payment.</li>\r\n	<li>Review supporting documents for accuracy and completion, according to IVSN policies and procedures, as well as GAAP.</li>\r\n	<li>Establish and maintain schedule for obtaining invoice and check approvals to process payments at least twice per week.</li>\r\n	<li>Reconcile processed work by verifying entries and comparing system reports to balances.</li>\r\n	<li>Charge expenses to proper accounts/projects/contracts by analyzing invoices and expense reports.</li>\r\n	<li>Prepare month-end accruals and AP journal entries.</li>\r\n	<li>Maintain accounting ledgers by verifying and posting account transactions.</li>\r\n	<li>Maintain historical records by filing documents, including digital copies.</li>\r\n	<li>Handle vendor account and GL account reconciliations.</li>\r\n	<li>Prepare allocation entries.</li>\r\n	<li>Manage vendor accounts with terms and maintenance process and resolve payment discrepancies.</li>\r\n	<li>Reconcile vendor statements with accounting system records for each period.</li>\r\n	<li>Process monthly corporate credit card transactions.<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b>Customer and Colleague Relations</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Maintain a positive, professional working relationship with vendors, landlords, and internal IVSN “customers”.</li>\r\n	<li>Respond in a timely manner with accurate attention to detail when handling inquiries from vendors and staff.</li>\r\n	<li>Collaborate with colleagues throughout IVSN in tracking budget expenses.</li>\r\n	<li>Proactively communicate with customers on issues resulting in a payment delay.</li>\r\n	<li>Produce special account statements or other reports as required or requested.</li>\r\n	<li>Assist in month-end, quarter-end, and year-end close processes as requested.</li>\r\n	<li>Provide back-up coverage to other accounting staff.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"> </span></b><b><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">QUALIFICATIONS</span></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Bachelor degree in Accounting, Finance, Economics, or Business Administration - or equivalent directly-related work experience</li>\r\n	<li>3 years of Accounts Payable experience, AP role at nonprofit ideal</li>\r\n	<li>Solid communication, interpersonal, customer service, and relationship building skills</li>\r\n	<li>Ability to work independently and also as a contributing team member</li>\r\n	<li>Flexibility to meet deadlines during peak workload periods</li>\r\n	<li>Familiarity with accounting software implementations, particularly migration of AP vendors and open invoices from old to new (migration to new accounting software planned)</li>\r\n	<li>Experience using Blackbaud’s Financial Edge software a plus</li>\r\n	<li>Intermediate Microsoft Excel skills, regular user of Microsoft Office and Outlook</li>\r\n	<li>Satisfactory LiveScan results</li>\r\n	<li>Commitment to the mission of IVSN</li>\r\n</ul>','Accounts Payable Specialist','','publish','closed','open','','accounts-payable-specialist','','','2014-03-21 10:47:34','2014-03-21 17:47:34','',251,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=769',26,'page','',0),(771,12,'2014-03-25 17:32:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<h1>Test</h1>\r\n<a class=\"addthisevent\" title=\"Add to Calendar\" href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/event/volunteer-appreciation-events/\">\r\nAdd to Calendar\r\n<span class=\"_start\">22-04-2014 17:30:00</span>\r\n<span class=\"_end\">11-05-2014 19:00:00</span>\r\n<span class=\"_zonecode\">6</span>\r\n<span class=\"_summary\">IVSN Volunteer Appreciation Event</span>\r\n<span class=\"_description\">Meet and mingle with your fellow volunteers, get the latest news about programs at InnVision Shelter Network, and celebrate the huge impact volunteers like you make in helping homeless families and individuals return to self-sufficiency. Light drinks and refreshments will be served.</span>\r\n<span class=\"_location\">IVSN’s Montgomery Street Inn, 358 N Montgomery Street, San Jose, CA 95110</span>\r\n<span class=\"_date_format\">DD/MM/YYYY</span>\r\n</a>\r\n\r\n<!-- AddThisEvent -->\r\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://js.addthisevent.com/atemay.js\"></script>','Test','','draft','closed','open','','','','','2014-03-25 17:32:27','2014-03-26 00:32:27','',43,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=771',25,'page','',0),(773,12,'2014-03-26 10:49:40','2014-03-26 17:49:40','','Meal Provider Volunteer Manual 3-20-14','','inherit','closed','open','','meal-provider-volunteer-manual-3-20-14','','','2014-03-26 10:49:40','2014-03-26 17:49:40','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Meal-Provider-Volunteer-Manual-3-20-14.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(788,12,'2014-04-17 10:14:50','2014-04-17 17:14:50','','ivsn_newsletter_041514_web','','inherit','closed','open','','ivsn_newsletter_041514_web','','','2014-04-17 10:14:50','2014-04-17 17:14:50','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/ivsn_newsletter_041514_web.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(789,12,'2014-04-17 10:20:08','2014-04-17 17:20:08','','spring 2014 newsletter thumbnail','','inherit','closed','open','','spring-2014-newsletter-thumbnail','','','2014-04-17 10:20:08','2014-04-17 17:20:08','',250,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/spring-2014-newsletter-thumbnail.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(799,12,'2014-04-29 11:54:43','2014-04-29 18:54:43','<h1><a href=\"http://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/interns/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-678\" alt=\"apply internship button\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/apply-internship-button.png\" width=\"161\" height=\"51\" /></a>Donations Intern</h1>\r\n<strong>Location</strong>: IVSN Administrative Office, 181 Constitution Drive, Menlo Park, CA 94025\r\n\r\n<strong>Time Commitment</strong>: 9 weeks: June 16th – August 15th, Full or Part Time, minimum 20 hours/week\r\n<h2>Description</h2>\r\nEver left a bag of clothing at a nonprofit like Goodwill, and wondered where it went from there? How it benefited the low-income community, who ended up with it, and what the system was? The donations of items, called the “in kind” donations, is a complicated matrix of operations, with donations coming in daily at multiple locations, and flowing to where they are needed most in the organization.\r\n\r\nIVSN’s summer donations intern will be deeply involved in the inner workings of the in-kind donations operations. They will assist with creating structure and system, assessing needs and costs, and filling needs at programs throughout IVSN. The Donations Intern will be responsible for planning for and organizing incoming donations, working with donors who want to contribute, problem solving process roadblocks on a daily basis.\r\n<h2>Responsibilities</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Drafting a “needs list” that represents what programs are lacking</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Visiting shelter sites to access what donations they are receiving, what space they have to store donations, and how best to get things to them that they need</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Answering donor calls for information and furniture pick-ups</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Working with the maintenance team to deliver items to site that are needed</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Developing a system so that unneeded donations are removed from warehouses in a timely manner, and passed on to other partner organizations</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Position Requirements/Preferred Skills</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">HS Diploma and some college</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Profound attention to detail</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Very strong ability to plan and organize</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Highly proactive, with a diligent work ethic and positive attitude</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Ability to work with many people and teams across the agency</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Desire to learn and make a difference for people in IVSN’s programs </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Learning Outcomes</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Hands-on engagement with operations processes for one of the largest and most effective nonprofit agencies serving homeless populations in the SF Bay Area</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Insight into strategic decisions regarding operations, donors, and donation policy</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Career development opportunities, including networking with IVSN staff, donors, volunteers, and partner agencies </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Compensation:</b> Unpaid\r\n\r\n<b>Supervisor: </b>Program Manager, In-Kind Donations\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/interns/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-678 alignleft\" alt=\"apply internship button\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/apply-internship-button.png\" width=\"161\" height=\"51\" /></a>','Donations Intern','','publish','closed','open','','donations-intern','','','2014-04-29 11:54:43','2014-04-29 18:54:43','',632,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=799',38,'page','',0),(800,12,'2014-04-29 11:57:30','2014-04-29 18:57:30','<h1><a href=\"http://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/interns/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-678\" alt=\"apply internship button\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/apply-internship-button.png\" width=\"161\" height=\"51\" /></a>Safety Coordinator Intern</h1>\r\n<strong>Location</strong>: IVSN Administrative Office, 181 Constitution Drive, Menlo Park, CA 94025\r\n\r\n<strong>Time Commitment</strong>: 9 weeks: June 16th – August 15th, Full or Part Time, minimum 20 hours/week\r\n<h2>Description</h2>\r\nThe Safety Intern works with key members of the IVSN Safety team and assists with essential tasks including development of an agency wide safety policy and procedure manual, including safety and disaster prevention for 18 site based facilities, agency warehouses, and an administration office. The intern will also be involved with implementation of social media resources and procedures in IVSN safety policies and procedures.\r\n<h2>Responsibilities</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Developing a written safety policy and procedure manual</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Visiting shelter sites to access readiness</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Attending Safety Committee meetings</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Performing administrative duties</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Complete special projects as needed</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Position Requirements/Preferred Skills</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">HS Diploma and some college; bachelor’s degree preferred</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Strong interpersonal relationships</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Attention to detail</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Commitment to agency mission</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Highly organized</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Strong writing and computer skills</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Diligent work ethic, positive attitude, and desire to learn about non-profits and safety/disaster preparedness. </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Learning Outcomes</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Hands-on engagement in Development for one of the largest and most effective non-profit agencies serving homeless populations in the SF Bay Area</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Working knowledge of agency interdepartmental procedural development,</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Opportunities to practice teamwork and collaboration in a high-energy cooperative environment.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Networking opportunities for career development with InnVision Shelter Network staff and partner agencies</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Compensation:</b> Unpaid\r\n\r\n<b>Supervisor: </b>Lori Mangual, Senior Manager of Operations\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/interns/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-678 alignleft\" alt=\"apply internship button\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/apply-internship-button.png\" width=\"161\" height=\"51\" /></a>','Safety Coordinator Intern','','publish','closed','open','','safety-coordinator-intern','','','2014-04-29 11:57:30','2014-04-29 18:57:30','',632,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=800',37,'page','',0),(803,12,'2014-04-30 13:53:37','2014-04-30 20:53:37','','Meal Provider Volunteer Manual 4-30-14','','inherit','closed','open','','meal-provider-volunteer-manual-4-30-14','','','2014-04-30 13:53:37','2014-04-30 20:53:37','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Meal-Provider-Volunteer-Manual-4-30-14.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(811,12,'2014-04-02 13:23:18','2014-04-02 20:23:18','<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-812\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/madi-and-kinsey.png\" alt=\"madi and kinsey\" width=\"320\" height=\"231\" />For the Mascali family, volunteering is a family affair. Sisters Madi, 17, and Kinsey Mascali, 13, have been volunteering since they were toddlers, tagging along with their mother to serve dinners to homeless families at IVSN.\r\n\r\nIt wasn’t long before the two sisters launched their own volunteer initiative. In 2006, they started Packs With Love, collecting gently-used backpacks and school supplies to donate to IVSN families and to other homeless and foster children in the Bay Area.\r\n<h2>Packs With Love</h2>\r\nMadi and Kinsey wanted their donations to make children feel extra special, so they recruited more volunteers to help clean the backpacks to look fresh and new. The volunteers also put inspirational notes in the backpacks, along with notebooks, colored pens, and other school supplies.\r\n\r\n“A kid’s backpack is their identity on the first day of school. It makes you fit in,\" said Madi. \"If a kid feels equal to other kids on their first day of school, they have a chance to do well.”\r\n\r\nLast summer, the sisters collected 75 backpacks for homeless children at IVSN and distributed hundreds more to children throughout the Bay Area.\r\n<h2>Spreading Holiday Joy</h2>\r\nThe sisters enjoy getting to know the children at IVSN through their volunteer work. They recalled one fall evening while they were setting the table for dinner, when they asked what the children at the shelter were going to be for Halloween. They were stunned to hear that they didn’t have costumes.\r\n\r\n\"People think of homeless kids at Christmas, but who is helping them with a great Halloween costume or an Easter basket?” said Madi. The sisters immediately began plans to host Easter and Halloween parties for the children at IVSN.\r\n\r\nEach spring, Madi and Kinsey recruit their friends to host an egg hunt, serve dinner, and donate an Easter basket to each child. For Halloween, the girls come in costume, bringing dinner, games, and a costume for each child. They spend weeks collecting detailed costume requests, so that the 5-year-old who wants to be Batman gets his wish, cape and all.\r\n<h2>Volunteers For Life</h2>\r\nMadi and Kinsey spend over 450 hours a year volunteering their time to benefit IVSN. But their impact doesn’t stop there. They spread the volunteer bug throughout the community, recruiting their friends and soccer teams to join them at volunteer projects.\r\n\r\nKinsey says, \"I get asked all the time why I waste my summer volunteering. Then I spend the whole summer getting that friend to volunteer with me and converting them into a lifetime volunteer.”\r\n\r\nThe sisters have recently been awarded a special Volunteer Recognition Award from the Junior League of San Jose. They plan to continue their volunteer service at full speed, even as Madi begins to apply to college.\r\n\r\n\"We love InnVision Shelter Network because that is where we learned to volunteer,” said Kinsey. “We saw how just cooking a warm meal and playing with kids would make the moms smile. It makes us feel like we’re actually touching someone’s life.”\r\n\r\nTo donate a backpack and school supplies to Packs With Love, contact <a href=\"mailto:packswithlove@yahoo.com\" target=\"_blank\">packswithlove@yahoo.com</a>.','Sisters Volunteer Year After Year','','publish','closed','open','','sisters-volunteer-year-after-year','','','2014-05-08 13:25:13','2014-05-08 20:25:13','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=811',21,'post','',0),(812,12,'2014-05-08 13:23:29','2014-05-08 20:23:29','','madi and kinsey','','inherit','closed','open','','madi-and-kinsey','','','2014-05-08 13:23:29','2014-05-08 20:23:29','',811,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/madi-and-kinsey.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(813,12,'2014-05-08 13:25:07','2014-05-08 20:25:07','','madi and kinsey_thumbnail','','inherit','closed','open','','madi-and-kinsey_thumbnail','','','2014-05-08 13:25:07','2014-05-08 20:25:07','',811,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/madi-and-kinsey_thumbnail.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(814,12,'2014-04-15 13:25:24','2014-04-15 20:25:24','<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-815\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/marquise-murphy.png\" alt=\"marquise murphy\" width=\"320\" height=\"320\" />“Joining the Board with a client perspective is an important role for me,” said Marquise Murphy, a graduate of IVSN’s programs and recently-appointed member of the Board of Directors. “It shows people that if you take advantage of IVSN’s services, great things can happen.”\r\n\r\nMarquise’s resume includes a 6-year career in banking with companies like HSBC, JPMorgan Chase, and Wells Fargo. His passion had always been to work in real estate, so he moved to Florida to join his brother and pursue their dream of a family-owned real estate business.\r\n\r\nWhen his brother was offered a new job he couldn’t refuse, the family business folded. Marquise followed his back-up plan and secured a banking job in the Bay Area.\r\n\r\nJust as Marquise arrived in California, he discovered his job was no longer available. His financial security rapidly deteriorated, and he found himself homeless, waiting in line at a social services center. He was referred to IVSN’s Maple Street Shelter for adults in Redwood City.\r\n\r\nEach person Marquise met at the shelter defied his preconceived notions of homelessness. He met people who were hardworking and employed, struggling to keep up with rising housing costs. “It was a humbling experience,” he said.\r\n\r\nMarquise took advantage of all that IVSN had to offer, including meetings with his Case Manager, workshops, and connections to employers. He started working two part-time jobs, in addition to securing his California real estate license. With the help of his Case Manager, he eventually found an affordable studio apartment in San Carlos.\r\n\r\nMarquise is now self-sufficient, working as a realtor with Home Smart Platinum Living. He also serves as Vice Chair President of the Young Professionals Network of SAMCAR (San Mateo County Association of Realtors).\r\nIn February, Marquise joined the IVSN Board of Directors as a client graduate representative. “I want to give back. If I can inspire one person in a similar situation, I will feel very accomplished.”','Program Graduate Joins  Board of Directors','','publish','closed','open','','program-graduate-joins-board-of-directors','','','2014-05-08 13:29:32','2014-05-08 20:29:32','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=814',20,'post','',0),(815,12,'2014-05-08 13:29:13','2014-05-08 20:29:13','','marquise murphy','','inherit','closed','open','','marquise-murphy','','','2014-05-08 13:29:13','2014-05-08 20:29:13','',814,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/marquise-murphy.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(816,12,'2014-05-08 13:29:24','2014-05-08 20:29:24','','marquise murphy_thumbnail','','inherit','closed','open','','marquise-murphy_thumbnail','','','2014-05-08 13:29:24','2014-05-08 20:29:24','',814,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/marquise-murphy_thumbnail.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(817,12,'2014-04-23 13:29:47','2014-04-23 20:29:47','<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-818\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/noemi.png\" alt=\"noemi\" width=\"320\" height=\"231\" />As the mother of four boys between the ages of 3 and 10, Noemi has a quite a full plate. She had a steady job as a Medical Assistant at the Palo Alto Medical Foundation, when domestic violence forced her to find a new home for herself and her children.\r\n\r\nStrained by their unstable family situation, Noemi and her boys began to suffer from anxiety and depression. Noemi’s psychological health was so disabling that she was no longer able to work. With no job and no place to live, the family came to InnVision Shelter Network.\r\n\r\nNoemi’s Case Manager immediately connected her family with a psychiatric counselor. Her children received therapeutic counseling and participated in educational afterschool programming. Noemi attended regular group therapy sessions and workshops that teach “life skills” such as financial literacy, interview skills, and parenting—all led by IVSN volunteers.\r\n\r\nNoemi plans to find a new job as a Medical Assistant once she and her sons stabilize their mental health. With the help of her Case Manager, Noemi learned how to budget and save money. She has already put her tax refund into a savings account, which she plans to use for a deposit on an apartment and as an emergency fund—so that she and her boys never face homelessness again.','Homeless Mother Focuses on Mental Health Stability','','publish','closed','open','','homeless-mother-focuses-on-mental-health-stability','','','2014-05-08 13:52:02','2014-05-08 20:52:02','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=817',19,'post','',0),(818,12,'2014-05-08 13:51:30','2014-05-08 20:51:30','','noemi','','inherit','closed','open','','noemi','','','2014-05-08 13:51:30','2014-05-08 20:51:30','',817,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/noemi.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(819,12,'2014-05-08 13:51:42','2014-05-08 20:51:42','','noemi_thumbnail','','inherit','closed','open','','noemi_thumbnail','','','2014-05-08 13:51:42','2014-05-08 20:51:42','',817,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/noemi_thumbnail.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(822,12,'2014-05-08 14:13:54','2014-05-08 21:13:54','<h1>Housing Coordinator and Leasing Agent</h1>\r\n<strong>Position</strong>: Housing Coordinator and Leasing Agent: Menlo Park, CA\r\n\r\n<strong>Reports to</strong>: Program Manager: Permanent Supported Housing\r\n\r\n<strong>Hours: </strong>Full time – Mon-Fri\r\n\r\nInnVision Shelter Network (IVSN) is one of the largest and most effective providers of shelter/housing and supportive services across Silicon Valley and the San Francisco Peninsula. IVSN operates over 18 major sites from San Jose to Daly City, providing emergency, transitional, and permanent supportive housing, along with a breadth of supportive resources to help clients secure a place to call home. The organization serves thousands of homeless clients annually through its “Beyond the Bed” service model — a proven methodology that has historically delivered a 90% success rate in returning program graduates to permanent housing and self-sufficiency.\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION:</strong>\r\n\r\nInnVision Shelter Network is seeking an experienced property manager, program coordinator or leasing agent to help administer eight permanent supported housing and two transitional programs for homeless adults and families.\r\n\r\n<strong>DUTIES</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Housing Coordinator/Leasing agent will manage the day-to-day property management aspects for 10 programs across Santa Clara County and in Redwood City. All residents of the programs are homeless or formerly homeless. All are extremely low-income. Many qualify for permanent disability. Some are mentally ill and struggle with addiction challenges. The incumbent will:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Assist approved tenants with completing and submitting move-in paperwork</li>\r\n	<li>Collect and process monthly rents and program fees</li>\r\n	<li>Conduct annual eligibility re-certifications interviews with all tenants</li>\r\n	<li>Maintain property management files on all IVSN residential units</li>\r\n	<li>Under the direction of the Program Manager and Senior Director of Housing, coordinate all evictions.</li>\r\n	<li>Maintain positive relationships with landlords who master-lease housing units to IVSN</li>\r\n	<li>Coordinate services with Case Managers, Program Managers and other clinical and administrative staff</li>\r\n	<li>Participate in one-on-one and team meetings with the Permanent Supportive Housing Program Manager.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>EDUCATIONAL/SKILLS REQUIREMENTS:</strong>\r\n\r\nBA required, however non-profit housing/property management experience may be substituted for academic credentials. Prefer a minimum of two years experience as a property manager, leasing agent, or in some similar role for a non-profit or public housing program. Experience with marginalized, mentally ill and/or homeless populations is helpful. A thorough understanding of HUD programs, requirements and reporting is key. Must be able to research, read, and understand government housing contracts, specifically HUD and County contracts. Effective written and oral communication skills are necessary. Must be proficient in Microsoft programs; specifically, Word, Excel and Outlook. Must be willing to carry and use an IVSN Smartphone.\r\n\r\nMust be able to thrive independently in a fast-paced and deadline driven environment.\r\n\r\n<em>To apply, please submit your resume and a brief cover letter to <a href=\"mailto:jobs@ivsn.org\">jobs@ivsn.org</a>. Include the Job Title in the subject line. NO PHONE CALLS PLEASE. Thank you in advance to all applicants for their interest, time, and effort. InnVision Shelter Network is an Equal Opportunity Employer (EOE). Applicants are considered for employment without regard to age, race, color, religion, sex, national origin, sexual orientation, gender identity and gender expression, disability or veteran status.</em>','Housing Coordinator and Leasing Agent','','publish','closed','open','','housing-coordinator-and-leasing-agent','','','2014-08-05 16:16:00','2014-08-05 23:16:00','',251,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=822',24,'page','',0),(823,12,'2014-05-08 14:11:20','2014-05-08 21:11:20','<em><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-824\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/junior-league.png\" alt=\"junior league\" width=\"320\" height=\"231\" />By Shelly Welch, Junior League Volunteer</em>\r\n\r\nBefore you walk into a volunteer situation, there\'s always a certain distance you can place between yourself and the people you\'ve not yet met. It’s not that you are necessarily trying to draw lines in the sand; it’s that there’s a certain amount of trepidation when you are unsure of what to expect. No matter how well-prepared you are, no matter how many people you talk to, you are walking into an arena of a thousand possible outcomes. When you walk in, you are aware of what you know: your family, your life, your experiences. When you volunteer, you give yourself a moment to experience someone else\'s life.\r\n\r\nThat\'s why we volunteer. We find that no matter what we thought or expected walking in, we leave the experience transformed. We want to feel that we were able to make an impact.\r\n\r\nThe shelter committee provides an arena where Junior League women are able to lead Life Boost workshops with the women and men who live in two local shelters in run by InnVision Shelter Network: Haven House in East Palo Alto and First Step for Families in San Mateo. The workshops are short – only an hour. They are divided into short segments of time, career, and money management.\r\n\r\n\"What struck me most about the group who attended my session was how diverse it was – single mothers and their babies, middle-aged women, couples, and young adults.  I quickly realized that there was no cookie cutter advice that would pertain to each person but what was important was starting a conversation and taking 20 minutes to focus on career development. The group shared with each other what was working or not working for them and gave each other advice that was specific to their situation.  Several out of the group wrote down tips and went away with new ideas for landing jobs or moving up from their current positions. While none of us has all the answers, listening to each other and learning from others’ successes and failures is certainly a step in the right direction,\" says Stephanie Piecewicz of her experience.\r\n\r\nMost of us only barely understand what it means to be homeless. Our empathy may extend to a narrow space between new houses or apartments where we have to store our things for a week while we stay with friends or at a hotel until we can get everything sorted out. Whether or not we have a car is a choice we make and not a choice made for us. We have a safety net. We live in a world where we can always find a next step.\r\n\r\nMost of us have no concept of how easy it is for a person to become homeless. All it takes is one breaking point for things to start falling apart. A loss of income can be devastating if you can\'t find a way to get it back. What if you were laid off after having worked for 30 years and have no other skills or you have a disability that prevents you from working?  What if you have small children and no one to take care of them while you work?\r\n\r\nNicolette Frink says of her experience, \"They have been offered jobs, but the biggest struggle for them is finding one that will coincide with availability of their childcare options (and there are not a lot of options).  They are on wait-lists for affordable childcare but unfortunately the lists are years long.  Many of them want to return to school and were discussing financial aid opportunities (FAFSA) and other options to get them there.  It was clear they are taking advantage of every opportunity that comes their way and are doing their best to make a better life for themselves,\" says Nicolette Frink of her experience in the workshops.\r\n\r\nAt a recent workshop, I spoke to one woman who had had a well-paid job as a behavioral therapist. She\'s a single mother. She had her kids in daycare, she did the best she could. But her job was 9-6 and daycare was 8-3 and she\'d have to coordinate someone to pick up and watch her kids for the remainder of the afternoon. If her sitter couldn\'t make it or her parents couldn\'t (or wouldn\'t) help her, she\'d have to leave work. It was even worse if one of her kids would get sick. A few too many of these calls and suddenly she no longer had a job.\r\n\r\nImagine you are in an in-between moment. We all have them. These are moments between jobs or between apartments. These moments are stressful. They test us and our relationships with our families and friends. For us, though, these moments are only moments. We have an innate sense of a next step. We have a sense of a safety net, however strong or tenuous, and understand that no matter what that we can move forward.\r\n\r\nNow imagine you are in an in-between moment and that you can\'t figure out a next step.\r\n\r\nNow compound that with an environment where having a job does not guarantee that you can afford a place to live. Add a small child whose care makes it difficult for you to obtain a job. Add an addiction, physical ailment or mental illness. It would be difficult to face every day.\r\n\r\nI wonder how I would fare if I were in their shoes. I can’t imagine what life would be like if I had to plan as carefully or make important decisions as often as they have to. At the end of the sessions I lead, I like to take the last 3 minutes to tell them that I admire their courage. I say that I know few people who would survive such strong blows to their lives with such grace and care. My favorite part is seeing how such a small gesture on my part seems to lift their spirits.\r\n\r\nAs volunteers, our experiences vary immensely. “My first time working one of the instructional sessions for [InnVision Shelter Network] was intimidating.  I couldn’t pretend to be an expert in the topic that I was assigned, Careers, and wondered how I could possibly make a real difference to anybody,” says Stephanie. Sometimes we are leading workshops but aren’t so great at budgeting or time management, and we’re the ones taking notes. Sometimes, though, we can inspire. Sometimes we know exactly the right advice or the right venue that could really help a person achieve their dream. Mostly, though, we’re the ones coming away inspired. “It was very inspiring to see these women who, with baby in hand, living in a shelter, are not giving up on themselves or their families,” says Nicolette. “It almost felt selfish that I am volunteering my time, yet I am the one who leaves feeling uplifted and inspired. Interesting right?”','Volunteer Perspective: Walking into a Life Boost Workshop','','publish','closed','open','','volunteer-perspective-walking-into-a-life-boost-workshop','','','2014-05-08 14:11:20','2014-05-08 21:11:20','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=823',18,'post','',0),(824,12,'2014-05-08 14:11:02','2014-05-08 21:11:02','','junior league','','inherit','closed','open','','junior-league','','','2014-05-08 14:11:02','2014-05-08 21:11:02','',823,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/junior-league.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(825,12,'2014-05-08 14:11:13','2014-05-08 21:11:13','','junior league_thumbnail','','inherit','closed','open','','junior-league_thumbnail','','','2014-05-08 14:11:13','2014-05-08 21:11:13','',823,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/junior-league_thumbnail.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(826,12,'2014-05-08 14:37:17','2014-05-08 21:37:17','<h1>Case Manager, HCH</h1>\r\n<strong>Position</strong>: Healthcare for the Homeless Outreach Case Manager\r\n\r\n<strong>Location</strong>: San Mateo, CA\r\n\r\n<strong>Reports to</strong>: Assoc. Director of Housing Services\r\n\r\n<strong>Hours: </strong>40 hours, Varies by day\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION:</strong>\r\n\r\nInnVision Shelter Network is seeking an Outreach Case Manager who will work throughout the county identifying unsheltered and disabled homeless persons who would benefit from services. The Outreach Case Manager will be in the field 50% of the time, working to identify homeless people living in places not suitable for human habitation. Meeting Social Security deadlines and representing homeless disability claims are top priorities<strong>. </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>DUTIES</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Outreach</strong> <strong>Case Management: </strong>Provide outreach and case management services to unsheltered homeless individuals throughout San Mateo County. Identify target population and perform screening assessments and ongoing case management to assist participants to meet their goals. Provide information, referrals and crisis intervention as needed. Keep case files up-to-date, thorough, and accurate. Assist in compiling program statistics.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b><strong>Social Security Advocacy: </strong></b>Must learn the ins and outs of the Social Security disability application process and the best practices for helping homeless individuals through the process. Case Manager will be responsible for ensuring Social Security compliance from clients. Will be required to identify the disabling condition from medical records and write a summary and advocacy letter to supplement the application. Must have patience in helping clients understand the complicated processes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Benefit enrollment: </strong>Requires Case Manager to become state certified to be an Application Assistant. Will be screening and enrolling clients in state and local programs such as Medi-Cal and the San Mateo County health coverage program (ACE).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Program and Professional Development: </strong>It will be expected that the Case Manager will be active in developing this new outreach program. Includes looking for opportunities to grow the program, develop professional relationships and further develop best practices for the program.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Meetings and collaboration: </strong>Meet weekly with program staff to coordinate delivery of services. Meet weekly with Manager of Housing Services for supervision. Participate in meetings with other community agencies. Fill other requests as made by supervisor, including assistance across program lines. Work with part time Case Manager staff to achieve program goals</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Other: </strong>Assist in maintaining a clean and safe environment. Carry emergency beeper as necessary. Other related duties as assigned.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>EDUCATIONAL/SKILLS REQUIREMENTS:</strong>\r\n\r\nBachelor’s degree preferred. Strong writing and reasoning skills required. This is a training intensive position, therefore priority will be given to those willing to make a two year commitment to the program. Candidate must have excellent interpersonal skills and ability to interact effectively with other agencies. Prior experience with homeless or outreach a plus. Must understand and possess a willingness to learn the issues faced by low-income populations. Spanish-speaking preferred. Automobile, valid driver’s license and clean driving record required. Must be proficient in Microsoft Office.','Case Manager, HCH','','publish','closed','open','','outreach-case-manager-hch','','','2014-05-09 13:00:34','2014-05-09 20:00:34','',251,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=826',23,'page','',0),(827,12,'2014-05-08 14:39:23','2014-05-08 21:39:23','<h1>SSVF Program Manager</h1>\r\n<strong>Position</strong>: Supportive Services for Veteran Families (SSVF) Program Manager\r\n\r\n<strong>Location</strong>: San Mateo, CA\r\n\r\n<strong>Reports to</strong>: Senior Director of Housing\r\n\r\n<strong>Hours: </strong>Full time – Mon-Fri\r\n\r\n<strong>DESCRIPTION:                                                                       </strong>\r\n\r\nInnVision Shelter Network is seeking an experienced program manager to lead a team of clinicians providing homelessness prevention and rapid re-housing services to homeless Veterans and their familes.\r\n\r\n<strong>DUTIES</strong>\r\n\r\nThe SSVF Program Manager will manage the day-to-day operations of the Supportive Services for Veteran Families program in San Mateo County. The incumbent will:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Assign new cases and monitor case loads</li>\r\n	<li>Mange work-flow of Case Managers, Housing Outreach Associates and other staff.</li>\r\n	<li>Maintain positive relationships with the VA, agency partners, landlords and other stakeholders to support the SSVF program and IVSN in general.</li>\r\n	<li>Research, study and keep current on SSVF policies, procedures and guidance delivered by the VA.</li>\r\n	<li>Monitor the disbursal of Temporary Financial Assistance and Case Management Services delivered to Veterans and their families.</li>\r\n	<li>Prepare quarterly financial and narrative reports</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>EDUCATIONAL/SKILLS REQUIREMENTS:</strong>\r\n\r\nMaster’s degree in social work or related field preferred; BA in social work or a related field required; professional experience may be substituted for lack of academic credentials. Minimumtwo years experience in serving homeless families and/or individuals in crisis. Excellent interpersonal skills and ability to interact effectively with internal and external stakeholders required. Familiarity with issues of substance abuse, mental health, PTSD and Veteran’s issues required. Prior experience with homeless Veterans is a plus. Familiarity with VA programs preferred. Prior military experience helpful. Automobile, valid driver’s license and proof of insurance required.\r\n\r\nMust be able to thrive independently in a fast-paced and deadline driven environment.','SSVF Program Manager','','publish','closed','open','','ssvf-program-manager','','','2014-05-08 14:54:08','2014-05-08 21:54:08','',251,'http://www.ivsn.org/?page_id=827',22,'page','',0),(842,12,'2014-05-22 16:35:30','2014-05-22 23:35:30','','Rohan_Bafna','','inherit','closed','open','','rohan_bafna','','','2014-05-22 16:35:30','2014-05-22 23:35:30','',665,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Rohan_Bafna.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(846,12,'2014-05-28 10:27:50','2014-05-28 17:27:50','','IVSN-Breakfast-Sponsor-Recognition-Oct-9-2014v2','','inherit','closed','open','','ivsn-breakfast-sponsor-recognition-oct-9-2014v2','','','2014-05-28 10:27:50','2014-05-28 17:27:50','',49,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/IVSN-Breakfast-Sponsor-Recognition-Oct-9-2014v2.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(850,12,'2014-05-28 11:14:50','2014-05-28 18:14:50','','RegisWeb','','inherit','closed','open','','regisweb','','','2014-05-28 11:14:50','2014-05-28 18:14:50','',49,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/RegisWeb.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(851,12,'2014-05-28 17:03:21','2014-05-29 00:03:21','','IVSN-Breakfast-Table-Host-Recognition','','inherit','closed','open','','ivsn-breakfast-table-host-recognition','','','2014-05-28 17:03:21','2014-05-29 00:03:21','',49,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/IVSN-Breakfast-Table-Host-Recognition.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(853,12,'2014-06-02 16:39:53','2014-06-02 23:39:53','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-854\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/VA-Award.png\" alt=\"VA Awards\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" />Congratulations to staff at Montgomery Street Inn and Maple Street Shelters for receiving 5 awards from the VA for service to veterans!</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We were honored to have case managers Angelica Naranjo and Chelsea Hunter and our programs at Montgomery Street Inn recognized at the event. IVSN’s CEO Karae Lisle and VP of Programs Dr. Brian Greenberg also received Outstanding Community Partner awards, presented for excellent service and for their receptiveness to new ideas.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">IVSN operates 9 emergency and transitional shelters for homeless single adults and families, including Veterans. These shelters offer a safe, supportive community for residents while they work toward regaining housing.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/services/veteran-services/\">Click here</a> to learn more about how IVSN is helping Veterans and their families return to self-sufficiency and permanent housing.</p>','IVSN Awarded for Veterans Services at VA Event','','publish','closed','open','','ivsn-awarded-for-veterans-services-at-va-event','','','2014-06-03 12:00:43','2014-06-03 19:00:43','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=853',17,'post','',0),(854,12,'2014-06-02 16:31:52','2014-06-02 23:31:52','','','','inherit','closed','open','','va-award','','','2014-06-02 16:31:52','2014-06-02 23:31:52','',853,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/VA-Award.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(855,12,'2014-06-03 12:00:17','2014-06-03 19:00:17','','VA-Awardssmall','','inherit','closed','open','','va-awardssmall','','','2014-06-03 12:00:17','2014-06-03 19:00:17','',853,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/VA-Awardssmall.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(858,12,'2014-06-06 16:29:20','2014-06-06 23:29:20','','Donation Wish List 060614','','inherit','closed','open','','donation-wish-list-060614','','','2014-06-06 16:29:20','2014-06-06 23:29:20','',210,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Donation-Wish-List-060614.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(862,12,'2014-06-10 17:29:29','2014-06-11 00:29:29','','Donation Wish List 060614','','inherit','closed','open','','donation-wish-list-060614-2','','','2014-06-10 17:29:29','2014-06-11 00:29:29','',210,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Donation-Wish-List-0606141.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(864,12,'2014-06-16 11:55:25','2014-06-16 18:55:25','<iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/FMTz6qoP34k\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n\r\nDr. Brian Greenberg, IVSN’s Vice President of Programs, recently appeared on CBS’s regional news program “Bay Area Focus” to discuss our Beyond the Bed services, the individuals that we are helping, and the progress we see being made by our clients every day.','InnVision Shelter Network on \"Bay Area Focus\"','','publish','closed','open','','innvision-shelter-network-on-bay-area-focus','','','2014-06-17 13:38:12','2014-06-17 20:38:12','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=864',16,'post','',0),(865,12,'2014-06-17 13:37:59','2014-06-17 20:37:59','','greenberg','','inherit','closed','open','','greenberg-2','','','2014-06-17 13:37:59','2014-06-17 20:37:59','',864,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/greenberg.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(867,12,'2014-06-20 14:01:47','2014-06-20 21:01:47','','Meal Provider Volunteer Manual 4-30-14','','inherit','closed','open','','meal-provider-volunteer-manual-4-30-14-2','','','2014-06-20 14:01:47','2014-06-20 21:01:47','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Meal-Provider-Volunteer-Manual-4-30-14.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(868,12,'2014-06-23 17:27:34','2014-06-24 00:27:34','','Donation Wish List 062314','','inherit','closed','open','','donation-wish-list-062314','','','2014-06-23 17:27:34','2014-06-24 00:27:34','',210,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Donation-Wish-List-062314.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(879,12,'2014-07-02 17:41:40','2014-07-03 00:41:40','<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-884\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Regis_web.jpg\" alt=\"Regis_web\" width=\"200\" height=\"266\" />MENLO PARK, CA – InnVision Shelter Network (IVSN), a leading provider of housing and supportive services for homeless families and individuals on the Peninsula and in Silicon Valley, will host its annual <strong>Benefit Breakfast on Thursday, October 9th from 7:30am to 9:00am at the Hyatt Regency Hotel in Burlingame.</strong>\r\n\r\nThis year’s event program will include a keynote address by Emmy Award winning host, actor, singer, and author Regis Philbin. Since Philbin first stepped in front of the camera more than 50 years ago, he has become a noted and celebrated entertainment figure. Philbin has won many awards, including Emmys for his work on LIVE! with Regis and Kelly and Who Wants To Be A Millionaire, a TV Guide Award as Personality of the Year, and a Broadcasting &amp; Cable Lifetime Achievement Award.\r\n\r\nIn addition to his many accomplishments in the world of entertainment, Philbin is also a noted supporter of organizations that address homelessness and provide veteran and service member support.\r\n\r\n“Regis is such a talented performer with an incredibly rich and storied career and commitment to philanthropy,” says InnVision Shelter Network CEO Karae Lisle. “We are delighted to have him attend our event and entertain as well as inspire our audience.”\r\n\r\nThe Benefit Breakfast program will also feature Master of Ceremonies and FOX Sports anchor Ted Robinson, remarks from IVSN’s CEO Karae Lisle, award presentations to outstanding volunteers and supporters, and a testimonial by a client of one of IVSN’s shelters.\r\n\r\nIVSN’s Annual Benefit Breakfast is the largest event of its kind on the San Francisco Peninsula. This inspiring event promotes awareness about issues of homelessness in the Peninsula and Silicon Valley regions. Event sponsorships and day-of donations help fund IVSN’s housing programs and supportive services for homeless men, women, and children.\r\n\r\n<strong>For tickets, table host opportunities, and sponsorship information for the Benefit Breakfast, <a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/event/breakfast-burlingame/\">click here</a> or call (650) 685-5880 ext. 186.</strong>',' Regis Philbin to Deliver Keynote at InnVision Shelter Network’s Fall Benefit Breakfast ','','publish','closed','open','','regis-philbin-to-deliver-keynote-at-innvision-shelter-networks-fall-benefit-breakfast','','','2014-07-15 10:48:41','2014-07-15 17:48:41','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=879',15,'post','',0),(884,12,'2014-07-07 17:55:10','2014-07-08 00:55:10','','Regis_web','','inherit','closed','open','','regis_web','','','2014-07-07 17:55:10','2014-07-08 00:55:10','',879,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploa