llman@ivsn.org\">cbillman@ivsn.org</a>\n\n<a title=\"Montgomery Street Inn\" href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/services/single-adult-services/montgomery-street-inn/\"><strong>Montgomery Street Inn</strong></a>\n358 N Montgomery St. San Jose, CA 95110 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/rTDfn\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\nInterim and stabilization shelter and services for 85 single men\n<strong>Contact:</strong> Bob Hutchinson, 408-271-5160, bhutchinson@ivsn.org\n\n<strong>Stevens House</strong>\n435 S 10th Street, San Jose, CA 95112 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/cHrhV\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\nInterim housing for single men and women diagnosed with significant mental illness\n<strong>Contact:</strong> Sabrina Delgado, 650-222-7405, <a href=\"mailto:sdelgado@ivsn.org\">sdelgado@ivsn.org</a>\n\n<a title=\"Veterans Hoptel\" href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/services/veteran-services/veterans-hoptel/\"><strong>Veterans Hoptel</strong></a>\n2800 Illinois Street, East Palo Alto, CA 94303 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/LTx37\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\nShort-term housing for Veterans accessing VA medical services\n<strong>Contact:</strong> Craig Billman, 650-364-1150 ext. 514, <a href=\"mailto:cbillman@ivsn.org\">cbillman@ivsn.org</a>\n<h2>Multi-Service Center<b></b></h2>\n<a title=\"Opportunity Services Center\" href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/services/family-services/opportunity-services-center/\"><strong>Opportunity Services Center</strong></a>\n33 Encina Avenue, Palo Alto, CA 94301 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/MwVqn\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\nMulti-Service drop in center and permanent supportive housing for families and single adults. IVSN operates first-floor daily services center Monday-Friday, providing access to case management, meals, medical/dental services, laundry, transportation assistance, life skill classes, clothing closet, children’s activities, and computer lab.\n<strong>Contact:</strong> Philip Dah, 650-853-8672, <a href=\"mailto:pdah@ivsn.org\">pdah@ivsn.org</a>\n<h2>Permanent Supportive Housing</h2>\n<strong>Alexander House</strong><b></b>\n5775 Chandler Ct, San Jose, CA 95123 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/umuEl\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\nPermanent supportive housing for single women with mental illness\n<strong>Contact:</strong> Sabrina Delgado, 650-222-7405, <a href=\"mailto:sdelgado@ivsn.org\">sdelgado@ivsn.org</a>\n\n<strong>Hester Gardens</strong>\n1759 Hester Avenue, San Jose, CA 95128 (<a href=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=1759+Hester+Avenue,+San+Jose,+CA+95128&amp;hl=en&amp;sll=37.247357,-121.825351&amp;sspn=0.00977,0.022724&amp;gl=us&amp;hnear=1759+Hester+Ave,+San+Jose,+Santa+Clara,+California+95128&amp;t=m&amp;z=16\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\nPermanent supportive housing for single women with mental illness\n<strong>Contact:</strong> Sabrina Delgado, 650-222-7405, <a href=\"mailto:sdelgado@ivsn.org\">sdelgado@ivsn.org</a>\n\n<strong>Vendome</strong>\n415 E 2nd Avenue, San Mateo, CA 94401 (<a href=\"http://goo.gl/maps/QGSLu\" target=\"_blank\">map</a>)\nPermanent supportive housing for 16 single men and women\n<strong>Contact:</strong> Steve Carey, 650-619-8163, <a href=\"mailto:scarey@ivsn.org\">scarey@ivsn.org</a>\n\n<em>Additional 100+ permanent supportive housing units at scattered sites.</em>','Locations','','inherit','closed','closed','','238-autosave-v1','','','2015-10-12 13:46:09','2015-10-12 20:46:09','',238,'http://www.ivsn.org/238-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1559,12,'2015-10-12 13:38:25','2015-10-12 20:38:25','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-156\" src=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/ivsn_homeless_veteran_man-320x213.jpg\" alt=\"ivsn_homeless_veteran_man\" width=\"320\" height=\"213\" />Veterans Hoptel</h1>\r\nIVSN’s Veterans Hoptel provides 1-3 nights of shelter, along with case management and transportation, to low-income Veterans from out-of-town coming to receive medical care and/or assessment from the local Veterans hospital.<b></b>\r\n\r\nThe name “Hoptel” is play on the word “hotel”; a “hop” is a military term for a short stay.\r\n\r\nMany Veterans travel great distances to access world-class medical services at VA hospitals in Silicon Valley. With limited means, these Veterans cannot afford housing during their trip, and would be homeless without the assistance of the Hoptel program.\r\n\r\n<strong>Hoptel guests are provided:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Short term accommodations for 1-3 days in a safe, clean environment</li>\r\n	<li>Food and open kitchen</li>\r\n	<li>Access to laundry</li>\r\n	<li>Transportation assistance to medical appointments</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>For Hoptel Reservations, contact: </b>\r\n\r\nChristopher Lum, MSW, ACSW\r\n\r\n(650) 493-5000 ext 65456\r\n\r\n<b>For more info about the Hoptel, contact: </b>\r\n\r\nMariana Garcia at <a href=\"mailto:mgarcia@ivsn.org\">mgarcia@ivsn.org</a> or (650) 364-1150 ext. 511\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Veterans Hoptel','','inherit','closed','closed','','80-autosave-v1','','','2015-10-12 13:38:25','2015-10-12 20:38:25','',80,'http://www.ivsn.org/80-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1561,11,'2015-10-14 20:32:56','2015-10-15 03:32:56','<h1><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-403\" src=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/volunteer_food_meal_service-320x241.jpg\" alt=\"volunteer_food_meal_service\" width=\"320\" height=\"241\" />Meal Programs</h1>\nYour volunteer group can provide and serve healthy and nutritious meals to homeless families and individuals at several InnVision Shelter Network facilities.\n\nPlease note that we request your group buy and prepare the food for our clients; IVSN’s housing sites are not “soup kitchens,” and as such we ask volunteers to donate the food and their time to serve our clients.\n<h2>Meal Provider Volunteer Manual</h2>\nWe recommend you review the <a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Meal-Provider-Volunteer-Manual-020415.pdf\">Meal Provider Volunteer Manual</a> for site-specific details and guidance on how to ensure a fun and productive volunteer experience.\n<h2>Sign Up to Provide a Meal</h2>\nTo provide a meal for <strong>Commercial Street Inn </strong> in San Jose, view the <a href=\"http://volunteer.ivsn.org/IVSNCalendar.aspx?CLR=14\">Commercial Street Inn Meal Provider Calendar</a> and register for an available meal.\n\nTo provide a meal for <strong>First Step for Families</strong> in San Mateo, view the<a href=\"http://volunteer.ivsn.org/IVSNCalendar.aspx?CLR=9\"> First Step Meal Provider Calendar</a> and register for an available meal.\n\nTo provide a meal for <strong>Julian Street Inn</strong> in San Jose, view the <a title=\"Julian Street Inn Meal Provider Calendar \" href=\"http://volunteer.ivsn.org/IVSNCalendar.aspx?CLR=12\">Julian Street Inn Meal Provider Calendar</a> and register for an available meal. <b>Must be 18 years of age to volunteer at this site.</b>\n\nTo provide a meal for <strong>Maple Street Shelter </strong> in Redwood City, view the <a href=\"http://volunteer.ivsn.org/IVSNCalendar.aspx?CLR=15\">Maple St. Meal Provider Calendar</a> and register for an available meal.\n\nTo provide a meal for <strong>Montgomery Street Inn </strong>in San Jose, view the <a href=\"http://volunteer.ivsn.org/IVSNCalendar.aspx?CLR=13\">Montgomery Street Inn Meal Provider Calendar</a> and register for an available meal. <b>Must be 18 years of age to volunteer at this site.</b>\n\nTo provide a meal for <strong>Villa Shelter </strong> in San Jose, view the <a title=\"Villa Meal Provider Calendar\" href=\"http://volunteer.ivsn.org/IVSNCalendar.aspx?CLR=17\">Villa Meal Provider Calendar</a> and register for an available meal.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">To provide a meal for all other sites, please contact </span><span class=\"s1\">Jessie Ellington at <a href=\"mailto:Jellington@ivsn.org\"><span class=\"s2\">Jellington@ivsn.org</span></a></span><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">.</span>','Meal Programs','','inherit','closed','closed','','188-autosave-v1','','','2015-10-14 20:32:56','2015-10-15 03:32:56','',188,'http://www.ivsn.org/188-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1563,12,'2015-10-15 16:30:47','2015-10-15 23:30:47','','Case Manager MSI','','inherit','closed','closed','','case-manager-msi','','','2015-10-15 16:30:47','2015-10-15 23:30:47','',251,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Case-Manager-MSI.doc',0,'attachment','application/msword',0),(1564,12,'2015-10-15 16:31:27','2015-10-15 23:31:27','','Food Service Coordinator','','inherit','closed','closed','','food-service-coordinator','','','2015-10-15 16:31:27','2015-10-15 23:31:27','',251,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Food-Service-Coordinator.docx',0,'attachment','application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document',0),(1566,11,'2015-10-18 21:57:22','2015-10-19 04:57:22','','IVSN-SecuritiesTransferRequestForm-RBC_UPDATED','','inherit','closed','closed','','ivsn-securitiestransferrequestform-rbc_updated','','','2015-10-18 21:57:22','2015-10-19 04:57:22','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/IVSN-SecuritiesTransferRequestForm-RBC_UPDATED.docx',0,'attachment','application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document',0),(1568,11,'2015-10-22 21:09:52','2015-10-23 04:09:52','<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Meet the Cervantes Family</h1>\n[embed]http://youtu.be/tfLnf2uIIhE[/embed]\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">For more stories of success, read our <a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/holiday-appeal-2014/\">Holiday Appeal</a>.</h1>\n<a href=\"https://14345.thankyou4caring.org/sslpage.aspx?pid=392\"><img class=\"wp-image-452 size-full aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/donate_button.png\" alt=\"donate_button\" width=\"161\" height=\"51\" /></a>','Meet the Cervantes Family','','inherit','closed','closed','','1142-autosave-v1','','','2015-10-22 21:09:52','2015-10-23 04:09:52','',1142,'http://www.ivsn.org/1142-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1569,11,'2015-10-23 16:09:20','2015-10-23 23:09:20','','Case Manager RFH_October 2015','','inherit','closed','closed','','case-manager-rfh_october-2015','','','2015-10-23 16:09:20','2015-10-23 23:09:20','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Case-Manager-RFH_October-2015.doc',0,'attachment','application/msword',0),(1572,12,'2015-11-03 14:55:32','2015-11-03 22:55:32','<img class=\"alignright wp-image-1584 size-medium\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/IMG_6231-edit-320x236.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" height=\"236\" />\n<h1>NextGen Advisory Board</h1>\n<h2>IVSN\'s NextGen Advisory Board brings together young professional leaders who are socially conscious and striving to make an impact.</h2>\nThe NextGen Advisory Board, founded in January 2014, uses the skills of its diverse membership to develop and execute functional projects based on the needs of IVSN, driving both strategic and tactical innovation for the agency.\n\nThe NextGen Board strives to increase awareness and educate the young professional population of Silicon Valley about the severity of homelessness in our community and about the successful methods IVSN has employed to tackle homelessness and poverty.\n<div align=\"center\">\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n</div>\n<h2>Members</h2>\nThe NextGen Advisory Board membership is made up of strong professional and academic backgrounds;  the composition of the board includes a variety of professionals from large tech companies, emerging growth companies, venture capital firms, law firms, and social sector organizations. Additionally, diversity in gender, country of origin, and professional titles make up this board composition.\n\n<a href=\"#MichaelHeadley\"><b>Michael Headley</b></a>, Digital Realty, Board Co-Chair\n\n<a href=\"#SarahBoisseree\"><b>Sarah Boisseree</b></a>, Financial Analyst at NetApp, Board Co-Chair\n\n<a href=\"#AdamKlein\"><b>Adam Klein</b></a>, Senior Manager of Strategic Initiatives at InnVision Shelter Network, Staff Liaison\n\n<a href=\"#RohanBafna\"><b>Rohan Bafna</b></a>, Microsoft XBox\n\n<a href=\"#FaustoBustos\"><b>Fausto Bustos</b></a>, PhD Student at UC Berkeley School of Public Health Student\n\n<a href=\"#KalaChapman\"><b>Kala Chapman</b></a>, Google\n\n<a href=\"#LisaAnneChung\"><b>Lisa-Anne Chung</b></a>, Senior Product Manager at Upwork\n\n<a href=\"#JuliaDuncan\"><b>Julia Duncan</b></a>, Foreign Affairs Officer at U.S. Department of State\n\n<a href=\"#CasandraEspinoza\"><b>Casandra Espinoza</b></a>, Founder of Share Ave\n\n<a href=\"#MarshallFisher\"><b>Marshall Fisher</b></a>, Associate Investment Director at Cambridge Associates\n\n<a href=\"#AllenHe\"><b>Allen He</b></a>, Senior Corporate Strategy Analyst at NetApp\n\n<a href=\"#WillLindemann\"><b>Will Lindemann</b></a>, Director of Growth at Branch Metrics\n\n<a href=\"#PromeetMansata\"><b>Promeet Mansata</b></a>, Product Manager at @WalmartLabs\n\n<a href=\"#StefanMoser\"><b>Stefan Moser</b></a>, Scientist at Amyris Inc.\n\n<a href=\"#MattPesko\"><b>Matt Pesko</b></a>, Resident in Psychiatry at Stanford Hospital and the Veteran\'s Administration Hospital\n\n<a href=\"#SeanTaube\"><b>Sean Taube</b></a>, Attorney at Wilson Sonsini Goodrich &amp; Rosati\n\n<a href=\"#ElizabethWoodson\"><b>Elizabeth Woodson</b></a>, Stanford University Student\n<div align=\"center\">\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n</div>\n<h2>Get Involved</h2>\n<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/forms/d/13cRFl6RxlnTrz7SYmFIN8t-_CU4Wqz3UWpIobxxpGBw/viewform\" target=\"_blank\">Fill out this short form</a> to connect with NextGen! One of our members will contact you shortly.\n<div align=\"center\">\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n</div>\n<h2>Press</h2>\n<strong>July 29, 2014 </strong>- San Mateo County Times - <a href=\"http://www.mercurynews.com/san-mateo-county-times/ci_26237326/margaret-lavin-innvision-shelter-network-and-linkedin-partner\">InnVision Shelter Network and LinkedIn Partner to Assist Bay Area Homeless in Search for Employment</a>\n\n<strong>July 18, 2014 </strong>- Mountain View Voice - <a href=\"http://www.mv-voice.com/news/2014/07/18/linkedin-to-hold-job-preparation-clinic-for-homeless\">LinkedIn to hold job preparation clinic for homeless</a>\n\n<strong>March 17, 2014 </strong>- San Mateo Daily Journal - <a href=\"http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/lnews/2014-03-17/next-generation-targeting-homelessness-nonprofit-forms-youth-advisory-board-of-young-and-educated-high-tech-professionals/1776425119831.html\" target=\"_blank\">Next generation targeting homelessness: Nonprofit forms youth advisory board of young and educated high-tech professionals</a>\n\n<strong>March 17, 2014</strong> - The Almanac - <a href=\"http://www.almanacnews.com/news/2014/03/17/innvision-creates-new-advisory-board\" target=\"_blank\">Menlo Park\'s InnVision creates NextGen Advisory Board</a>\n\n<strong>March 6, 2014</strong> - Silicon Valley Business Insider - <a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2014/03/06/young-googlers-venture-capitalists.html?page=all\" target=\"_blank\">Young Googlers, VCs, an Oakland Raider team up to tackle Silicon Valley homelessness</a>\n\n<strong>March 3, 2014</strong> - Yahoo Finance - <a href=\"http://finance.yahoo.com/news/innvision-shelter-network-creates-young-153000045.html\" target=\"_blank\">InnVision Shelter Network Creates Young Community Leaders Board to Tackle Local Homelessness</a>\n<div align=\"center\">\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n</div>\n<h2>NextGen Board Bios</h2>\n<img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-706\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/headley.png\" alt=\"headley\" width=\"103\" height=\"141\" /><b id=\"MichaelHeadley\">Michael Headley</b>, Digital Realty\n\nMichael Headley serves as the Co-Chair of the IVSN NextGen Advisory Board, focusing on supply chain optimization, cost reduction, and technology integration. Headley currently works at Digital Realty mapping business processes and identifying opportunities for automation and efficiency through enhanced technology. His passion for serving the community comes from a core belief that all people deserve the opportunity to lead a rewarding and fulfilling life, especially those in in need. Headley holds a BS in Electrical Engineering from the University of Virginia.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1373\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Sarah-Boisseree-320x435.jpg\" alt=\"OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA\" width=\"103\" height=\"140\" /><b id=\"SarahBoisseree\">Sarah Boisseree</b>,<b id=\"SarahBoisseree\"> </b>NetApp\n\nSarah Boisseree serves as the Co-Chair of the NextGen Board and works as a Financial Analyst at NetApp, a data storage and management company. She graduated from Stanford University in 2013 with a B.S. in Management Science and Engineering. At Stanford, Sarah was a Resident Assistant and a member of the executive council for her sorority. Previously, Sarah held summer internships at the public accounting firm PwC and with the Stanford Graduate School of Business Executive Education program. She first became involved with IVSN in high school as a volunteer at IVSN\'s First Step for Families in her hometown of San Mateo, CA. Sarah is also a finance advisor and a marketing advisor to collegiate chapters of her sorority. In her free time, Sarah enjoys reading, photography, traveling, and watching professional cycling.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1591\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdamKlein-1280x800.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"131\" /><b id=\"AdamKlein\">Adam Klein</b>,<b id=\"AdamKlein\"> </b>InnVision Shelter Network\n\nAdam Klein serves as the Staff Liaison and is a founding member of the NextGen Advisory Board, and works at IVSN as the Programs and Services Initiatives Manager. Klein graduated Phi Beta Kappa and with Distinction from Stanford University in 2013 with a degree in International Relations, where he was a Tour Guide Student Manager, an Admissions Associate, and a Resident Assistant. Previously, Klein was the Event Chair of the American Cancer Society\'s Relay for Life in his hometown of Burlingame, CA, served as the Student Member of the San Mateo Union High School District Board of Trustees, and worked as a Regional Director for Students for Barack Obama.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-842 size-full\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Rohan_Bafna.png\" alt=\"RohanBafna\" width=\"103\" height=\"138\" /><b id=\"RohanBafna\"></b>\n\n<b id=\"RohanBafna\">Rohan Bafna</b>,<b id=\"RohanBafna\"> </b>Microsoft XBox\n\nRohan Bafna currently works at Microsoft XBox as an Engineering Manager. He is also currently pursuing his MBA from the Haas School of Business at UC Berkeley. He holds a Masters in Computer Engineering from New Jersey Institute of Technology. He has been an active volunteer for Vibha since 2006 playing various roles including most notably the co-ordinator of the Atlanta Chapter and the race director for Atlanta and Bay Area DreamMile events separately. He enjoys travelling, reading, ice-skating, and amateur photography.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1593\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Picture1-21.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"136\" /><b id=\"FaustoBustos\">Fausto Bustos</b>, UC Berkeley School of Public Health Student\n\nFausto Bustos is a second-year PhD student in Infectious Disease Epidemiology at the UC Berkeley School of Public Health. He is concurrently pursuing a Master\'s degree in Biostatistics. His doctoral work will focus on the transmission of dengue and other viral tropical diseases in Nicaragua. He graduated from Stanford University with degrees in Human Biology and Political Science, conducting research in molecular biology and political communications. He also received a Masters of Epidemiology from the Harvard School of Public Health, studing the transmission of influenza from poultry to humans while there. He has previously worked at the US State Department, and is currently a Guest Researcher at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. He is also a co-founder and senior consultant at College Aces, LLC, a college admissions consulting firm.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-704\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/cardona.png\" alt=\"cardona\" width=\"103\" height=\"141\" /><b id=\"AngelinaCardona\">Angelina Cardona</b>,<b id=\"AngelinaCardona\"> </b>Yale School of Management Student\n\nAngelina Cardona is currently a first-year MBA student at the Yale School of Management. She formerly worked as a Technical Recruiter for Google and for the Office of Alcohol Policy &amp; Education at Stanford University as an Assistant Director and Community Engagement Manager where she founded and implemented “Cardinal Nights” – an initiative to change campus alcohol culture. Originally from Sparks, Nevada, Cardona earned her B.A. in International Relations from Stanford University in 2011. During her senior year, she was elected the Student Body President.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<b id=\"KalaChapman\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1383\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/10295458_10103190012326533_8529739021541976129_o1-320x421.jpg\" alt=\"10295458_10103190012326533_8529739021541976129_o\" width=\"103\" height=\"136\" />Kala Chapman</b>, Google\n\nKala Chapman currently works as a Product Marketing Manager at Google, focusing on their Play Store efforts, where she has been since 2011. Before Google, she worked as an Associate for Entrepreneurial Services at Keiretsu Forum, a small private equity group operating out of the Bay Area. She first discovered a passion for the intersection of technology and social entrepreneurship as a Summer Associate for Samasource, a non-profit technology startup providing tech-based jobs to impoverished women and youth throughout India and Sub-Saharan Africa. She hails from Loomis, California and holds a B.A. from UC Berkeley in International Relations &amp; Global Poverty. When she’s not working, Kala enjoys trail running, baking and reading in the various parks San Francisco has to offer.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<b id=\"LisaAnneChung\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1585\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/D4F2683-684x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"154\" />Lisa-Anne Chung</b>, Upwork\n\nLisa-Anne is currently a Sr. Product Manager at Upwork and recently finished her MBA at UC Berkeley - Haas. At Upwork, a freelancer market place, she owns the Collaboration platform which recently successfully built and launched a new communication system. Prior to Upwork, she spent seven years at Intuit in various roles across Finance, Operations, Mobile Product Management, Customer Service Design, and Product Management. She is passionate about creating awesome customer experiences, improving existing processes, and finding more efficient and effective solutions to create delight for all stakeholders. Her undergraduate degree was in Management Science from the University of California, San Diego.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1592\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/juliaduncan.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"154\" /><b id=\"JuliaDuncan\">Julia Duncan</b>, U.S. Department of State\n\nJulia Duncan is a founding member and former chair of the IVSN NextGen Advisory Board. Duncan currently works on issues related to global food security at the State Department. Previously, she has worked at Google in the Finance Department, in the White House in the Office of Presidential Personnel, and on Capitol Hill as an aide. Additionally, she served on the 2008 Presidential Inaugural Committee and helped execute the MLK National Day of Service. Duncan holds her BA in Government and History from the University of Virginia and her MA in Public Management from Johns Hopkins University.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-705\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/espinoza.png\" alt=\"espinoza\" width=\"103\" height=\"141\" /><b id=\"CasandraEspinoza\">Casandra Espinoza</b>, Share Ave\n\nCasandra Espinoza is a founding member of the IVSN NextGen Advisory Board. She recently started Share Ave, a way for parents to hire early childhood specialists, not babysitters. She previously worked at Greylock Partners, a venture firm that focuses on consumer and enterprise investments. Casandra also participated in the Kauffman Fellows Program as a member of Class 16. Upon completion of the Kauffman program, she was the recipient of a peer selected award for class leadership. She holds a BA in Public Policy from Stanford University.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1589\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Marshall-Fisher1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"140\" /><b id=\"MarshallFisher\">Marshall Fisher</b>, Cambridge Associates\n\nMarshall Fisher is an Associate Investment Director in Cambridge Associates’ Menlo Park office, where he works with non-profit endowments to help them invest so they can fulfill their missions. He also volunteers as a tutor at Eastside College Preparatory School, an organization committed to opening new doors for students underrepresented in higher education. He is a 2011 graduate from Claremont McKenna College, where he majored in Economics, Environmental Science, and Political Science, and was a four-year member and two-year captain of the Men’s Varsity Soccer Team. Marshall is originally from Des Moines, Iowa, and in his free time enjoys the outdoors, bocce, piano, and film.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1588\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/29456661.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"139\" /><b id=\"AllenHe\">Allen He</b>, NetApp\n\nComing from Houston, Texas, Allen received a degree in Business Administration from UC Berkeley. IVSN is the first non-profit organization he is involved in on a professional level. He enjoys playing basketball, supporting the Houston Rockets, and snowboarding. He currently works in corporate strategy at NetApp, a data management and storage company in the bay area.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<b id=\"WillLindemann\"><b id=\"WillLindemann\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1379\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Lindemann-Headshot.png\" alt=\"Lindemann Headshot\" width=\"103\" height=\"112\" /></b></b>\n\n<b id=\"WillLindemann\"><b id=\"WillLindemann\">Will Lindemann</b></b>, Branch Metrics\n\nWill enjoys working at a local level with IVSN’s NextGen board, in addition to work he does with Children International, a global nonprofit. He\'s an ex-Googler who worked on the Chromecast team before leaving Google to join Branch Metrics, as Director of Growth. He holds a B.A. in Human Biology and a minor in English from Stanford University. In his spare time Will goes to Stanford games, hunts for interesting coffee shops and enjoys local and international adventures.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<b id=\"PromeetMansata\">Promeet Mansata</b>, @WalmartLabs<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1376\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Promeet-320x416.jpg\" alt=\"Promeet\" width=\"103\" height=\"134\" />\n\nPromeet Mansata currently works at @WalmartLabs as a Product Manager. He holds an MBA from the Haas School of Business at UC Berkeley and a Bachelor of Commerce and Master of Commerce from Bangalore University, India. He was one of the 15 winners of the LinkedIn Transformation Grant in 2014 and served as a coach for the 2105 grants cycle at LinkedIn. Promeet has also been a volunteer at Second Harvest Food bank since 2008. He is an avid runner and loves reading.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1590\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/headshot_kind_of2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"153\" /><b id=\"StefanMoser\">Stefan Moser</b>, Amyris Inc.\n\nStefan grew up in Switzerland and moved to San Mateo when he was 10, spending most of his youth on the Peninsula. He graduated from UCSD in 2011 and promptly moved back to the bay area to pursue opportunities in the biotech industry. Since his move back, he has moved around from San Mateo to San Francisco until finally settling in North Berkeley, where he works at Amyris Biotech, which specializes in producing alternatives to petroleum based products via a synthetic biology technology platform. Stefan is passionate about supporting IVSN and its mission to aid and support the homeless in the bay area.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<b id=\"MattPesko\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1377\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Matt-Pesko-320x401.jpg\" alt=\"Matt Pesko\" width=\"103\" height=\"129\" />Matt Pesko</b>,<b id=\"MattPesko\"> </b>Stanford Hospital and the Veteran\'s Administration Hospital\n\nMatt Pesko is currently a resident physician in the Stanford Department of Psychiatry working at Stanford Hospital and the Veteran\'s Administration Hospital. He completed medical school at Harvard University and a received a B.S. from the University of Wisconsin-Madison. His interest in combating homelessness started during a year of volunteer service through the Jesuit Volunteer Corps in which he worked with homeless individuals with mental illness and substance dependence in Portland, Maine. Pesko is originally from northern Wisconsin. In his free time, he enjoys reading and following professional baseball. He and his wife are also regular volunteers at the St. Anthony\'s Padua Dining Room in Redwood City.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-710\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/taube.png\" alt=\"taube\" width=\"103\" height=\"141\" /><b id=\"SeanTaube\">Sean Taube</b>,<b id=\"SeanTaube\"> </b>Wilson Sonsini Goodrich &amp; Rosati\n\nSean Taube is a founding member of the IVSN NextGen Advisory Board. Sean Taube is an attorney at Wilson Sonsini Goodrich &amp; Rosati. Prior to law school, Sean worked as an investment associate for several real estate investment firms. Sean also serves on the Taube Foundation for Jewish Life and Culture Advisory Board. Sean holds a BA from the University of California, Santa Barbara and a JD from University of San Francisco School of Law. Sean is a native of the Peninsula.\n\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"2\" width=\"100%\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-712\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/woodson.png\" alt=\"woodson\" width=\"103\" height=\"141\" /><b id=\"ElizabethWoodson\">Elizabeth Woodson</b>,<b id=\"ElizabethWoodson\"> </b>Stanford University Student\n\nElizabeth Woodson is currently serving as Student Body President of Stanford University, where she is studying Science, Technology and Society. She is a Mayfield Fellow, and is pursuing research on women and leadership in the non-profit sector. In addition to being Social Impact Manager for the student government, Woodson serves on the Board of Trustees\' Committee on Development and writes an opinions column for the Stanford Daily. Joining the IVSN NextGen Advisory Board is an exciting opportunity for Woodson, who spent three years facilitating weekly Theatre of the Oppressed sessions with women at New Haven\'s largest homeless shelter.','NextGen','','inherit','closed','closed','','665-autosave-v1','','','2015-11-03 14:55:32','2015-11-03 22:55:32','',665,'http://www.ivsn.org/665-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1573,11,'2015-10-26 21:09:03','0000-00-00 00:00:00','[one_half]\r\n<h2 class=\"p2\"><span class=\"s1\"><b>Study: 1 in 30 U.S. Kids Were Homeless During 2013</b></span></h2>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Study authors say nearly 2.5 million American children experienced homelessness last year.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The number of homeless children in the United States surged by 8% in 2013 to nearly 2.5 million, according to a new study that attributes the record-breaking figure to a shortage of affordable housing and the lingering effects of a jobless economic recovery.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The report published Monday by the National Center on Family Homelessness combined the U.S. Department of Education’s existing estimate of homelessness among school-age children, 1.5 million, with independent tallies for younger children not yet at school. The revised total suggests that one in every 30 children in the U.S. experienced homelessness in 2013.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The study authors attribute the elevated rates of homelessness to a sluggish economic recovery, compounded by a housing market that has priced out unemployed and low income families. California, in particular, was hard hit with 527,000 homeless children, accounting for one-fifth of the national total. </span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">-Comment by Dan Kedmey, Time.com</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\"><a href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Report-on-Child-Homelessness-Nov-2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Click here to read the full report.</a>[/one_half][one_half_last]</h4>\r\n<h2 class=\"p1\"><strong>Holiday Appeal: Change the life of a homeless child in our community today! </strong></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Give to the IVSN Holiday Appeal. Help us reach our goal of $3,750,000 by December 31, 2014.</h3>\r\n<a href=\"https://14345.thankyou4caring.org/sslpage.aspx?pid=392\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1078\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Donate-Now-button-320x72.png\" alt=\"Donate Now button\" width=\"302\" height=\"68\" /></a>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"#appeal\">Appeal from the CEO, Karae Lisle</a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"#tiffany\">Tiffany\'s Story</a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"#more\">More Lives Changed</a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<h4><a href=\"#about\">About InnVision Shelter Network </a></h4>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1082 size-medium\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/DSC_7321-320x476.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_7321\" width=\"320\" height=\"476\" />\r\n\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n\r\n[full_width]\r\n\r\n<a name=\"appeal\"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"color: #eb9122;\">Appeal from the CEO, Karae Lisle</span></h2>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">November 2014</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Dear Friend,</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>We have a problem.</b> Last night, almost 7,000 men, women, and children in our community were unsheltered – homeless – sleeping in unsafe conditions, doubled up with relatives or friends, on the street, or in places not meant for human habitation. Many are employed and hardworking, but still can’t find affordable housing on modest incomes. They are families struggling financially after an illness. They are veterans trying to return to civilian life. They are us.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>But, there is good news. </b>Unlike so many social problems that seem to have no solution, homelessness can be solved in our community with your support. By combining our Beyond the Bed services with temporary housing, we provide intensive, individualized counseling in a safe living environment with the expectation that our clients will succeed in overcoming homelessness.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Our model works.</b> More than 90% of the families, and 70% of the individuals, who graduate from our programs return to permanent housing and self-sufficiency. InnVision Shelter Network clients attain success quickly, graduating to permanent housing in an average of 163 days, compared to a national average of 230 days.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><b>Transformational initiatives like ours require significant resources.</b> With your financial contribution we provide:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li class=\"p3\">Professional case managers, mental health specialists, and advocates to coach and counsel our clients on a 1-on-1 basis</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p3\">Educational life skills classes including job preparation and financial literacy workshops to give our clients the skills to succeed in the long term</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p3\">Housing facilities from Daly City to San Jose operating at capacity to help 1,000 people every day</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Your generous gift is urgently needed to meet our goal of $3,750,000 by December 31, 2014.</b>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Investing in the solution to homelessness has a spectacular return on the health of our community. Please consider creating positive change in the lives of your neighbors by giving to InnVision Shelter Network this holiday season.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Warmest regards,</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-333\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/karae-sig.jpg\" alt=\"karae-sig\" width=\"123\" height=\"61\" /></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Karae Lisle</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: left;\">CEO</p>\r\n<a name=\"tiffany\"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2 class=\"p1\"><span style=\"color: #eb9122;\">A life changed: Meet Tiffany\'s Family</span></h2>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1066 size-large\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/DSC_7315-1024x687.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_7315\" width=\"550\" height=\"368\" />\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Tiffany is a U.S. veteran who served in the Air Force. She was raising her three children, Russel, Victoria, and Mary, when she became a victim of domestic violence. She fled with her children and lived with different family members while she struggled to find the stability to get back on track.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Fortunately, the Veteran\'s Administration referred Tiffany to InnVision Shelter Network\'s First Step for Families transitional shelter. \"The name suits the place very well. First Step for Families felt like a home to us,\" Tiffany says. \"We were safe there.\"</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The family\'s case manager, Andrea, guided Tiffany and her children every step of the way back to self-sufficiency. Tiffany worked tirelessly. She was employed full-time, raising her three children, and constantly applying for housing opportunities. Her kids benefited from attending our Summer Adventure Camp, which provides children with access to field trips and educational STEM programs they may not have otherwise enjoyed.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">With the support of our dedicated staff, the family was able to able to graduate from our program and move into a townhome in Sunnyvale. \"It\'s nice to feel comfortable and grounded again,\" she explains. \"We have a nice landlord, our own rooms, and space,\" Tiffany beamed.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Tiffany has been working at Michael\'s, the craft store, for a year and a half, beginning as a sales associate, moving up to the position of cashier, and then earning a promotion to assistant manager. She also owns a jewelry business, complete with an online shop to showcase her handmade jewelry. She is working to grow her business and eventually become a vendor at craft fairs and festivals.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Tiffany\'s story sheds light on InnVision Shelter Network\'s success in changing lives in our community. Her success story is just one of thousands made possible by our effective model. Over 90% of the families and 70% of the individuals who graduate from our transitional housing programs return to permanent housing and ongoing self-sufficiency.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 class=\"p1\"><strong>Please make a difference this holiday season by making a <a href=\"https://14345.thankyou4caring.org/sslpage.aspx?pid=392\">personal investment</a> to change lives.</strong></h2>\r\n<a name=\"more\"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"color: #eb9122;\">More Lives Changed</span></h2>\r\n<h4>Meet Odie</h4>\r\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1072\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/odie2_website-320x308.jpg\" alt=\"odie2_website\" width=\"304\" height=\"284\" />\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\">Odie was homeless and had been living on the streets for 10 years. Even with stable employment as a food service worker at Stanford University, low and garnished wages kept him from finding affordable housing.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\">Outreach case manager, Roberto, found Odie on the streets and, over time, convinced him that he could secure housing. With Roberto\'s help, Odie recently moved into transitional housing.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\">Now, Odie participates in life-skills workshops and is moving quickly towards self-sufficiency. He can\'t wait to have a permanent home where his children and grandchildren can visit him.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #751b53;\"><b><i>\"InnVision Shelter Network gives me hope. They help me remain focused and motivate me to reach my goals. For that I am truly grateful.\" - Odie</i></b></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Meet the McEvoy Family</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1073\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/McEvoy_IC-edits-320x209.jpg\" alt=\"McEvoy_IC edits\" width=\"331\" height=\"223\" />Angela and Jose became homeless when Jose\'s hours were drastically cut and Angela went on maternity leave to have their son, Julian.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\">With the help of her case manager, Angela enrolled in De Anza College and is earning a certificate in Medical Billing and Coding. The McEvoy family\'s determination is helping them succeed.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\">The McEvoy\'s graduated from our program and now live in an apartment in Redwood City. Angela works as a Senior Care Provider with Senior Helpers, and Jose has regained his hours as a truck driver.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #751b53;\"><b><i>\"We thank InnVision Shelter Network for giving us the opportunity for a fresh start.\" - Jose</i></b></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class=\"p1\"> Meet Vannessa\'s Family</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1074\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Vanessa_Website.jpg\" alt=\"Vanessa_Website\" width=\"251\" height=\"252\" />Vannessa and her daughter, Athina, became homeless at the end of a tumultuous family break-up; without a second income, Vannessa could no longer afford rent in San Mateo County.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\">As part of our program, Vannessa was required to save 50% of her income. She worked hard at Starbucks and saved nearly $10,000.</li>\r\n	<li class=\"p1\">Vannessa and Athina have now graduated from our program and live in an apartment in San Mateo. Vannessa is working towards earning a degree in Early Childhood Development, with plans to pursue a career in Social Work.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #751b53;\"><b><i>\"You never know what life can bring. InnVision Shelter Network\'s program has made me stay in the present and stay grounded for my daughter.\" - Vannessa</i></b></span></p>\r\n<a name=\"about\"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"color: #eb9122;\">About InnVision Shelter Network</span></h2>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1077\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Holiday-Appeal_online-info-page1-823x1024.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"650\" height=\"808\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>Follow our Progress</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/InnVisionShelterNetwork\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-98 size-full\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/facebook.png\" alt=\"facebook\" width=\"22\" height=\"21\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.facebook.cominnvisionshelternetwork\">innvisionshelternetwork</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/InnVisShelter\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-100 size-full\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/twitter.png\" alt=\"twitter\" width=\"22\" height=\"21\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/InnVisShelter\">@InnVisShelter</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">[/full_width]</p>','1 in 30 U.S. Kids Were Homeless During 2013. Change the life of a homeless child in our community today; Donate to IVSN’s Holiday Appeal','','draft','closed','open','','','','','2015-10-26 21:09:03','2015-10-27 04:09:03','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=1573',9,'post','',0),(1574,23,'2015-10-27 12:04:14','2015-10-27 19:04:14','<h1 class=\"p1\"></h1>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Generous support from the community during the holiday season is vital to creating a warm and meaningful experience </span><span class=\"s1\">for thousands of homeless adults and children in IVSN programs. Start planning now for ways you can help this year!</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Questions? Contact our Volunteer Associate Jessie Ellington at <a href=\"mailto:jellington@ivsn.org\"><span class=\"s2\">jellington@ivsn.org</span></a> or (650) 685-5880 ext. 180.<img class=\"wp-image-1504 aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Carolands-Holiday-Party_Children.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"300\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"1\" width=\"100%\" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h2>Give</h2>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>Give a Financial Contribution</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">IVSN relies on generous financial support from the community. Your gift ensures that we may continue to provide high quality, effective services year-round. <a href=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/donate/\">Donate Now</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>Donate in Honor of a Friend or Family Member</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Make a financial donation to IVSN in honor of a loved one. We will mail the honoree a special holiday card with artwork created by children at our shelters. <a href=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/donate/\">Donate Now</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\">Host a “Party with a Purpose”</a></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">In lieu of traditional presents, ask your friends, family, or coworkers to bring a cash gift for neighbors in need to your next holiday gathering.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\">Adopt-a-Household</a></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Every IVSN client participating in housing services will receive two holiday gift wishes. You can make these wishes come true by “adopting” a family or individual. Purchase a single gift, or shop for a whole family!</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\">Donate a Thanksgiving or Holiday Dinner Basket</a></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">With your donation of gift cards and/or dinner baskets, every family in IVSN programs will be able to enjoy a holiday meal together.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\">Host a Gift Drive</a></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Ask your friends, family or co-workers to bring gifts for homeless neighbors. Most needed items include gift cards ($30 value), linens, new socks and undergarments.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Volunteer</h2>\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\">Plan a Holiday Party at a Shelter</a></strong>\r\n\r\nHost a party or a “Cookies &amp; Carols” event at one of our shelter residences with your friends, coworkers, or volunteer group. A festive celebration makes the holidays bright and memorable for our clients.  <a href=\"http://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form43/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">\r\n</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Provide and Serve Holiday Meals</strong></a>\r\n\r\nGather a group of your friends or coworkers to provide and serve a special meal to our residents. On Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Eve, Christmas Day, New Year’s Eve, or New Year’s Day—in addition to weekends (Saturdays and Sundays) throughout the year.<a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\">\r\n</a>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Meal Provider Volunteer Manual\" href=\"http://www.ivsn.org/volunteer/meal-programs/\">Click here to find availability and sign up to provide a meal.</a>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form73/index.html?1444862360261\" target=\"_blank\">Decorate a Shelter</a></strong>\r\n\r\nVolunteer with a group of your friends or colleagues to bring in decorations and turn a shelter into a winter wonderland. <a href=\"http://www.formsite.com/shelternetwork/form43/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">\r\n</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Plan Your Holiday Giving and Volunteering Now!','','publish','closed','open','','volunteer-opportunities-holidays-2015','','','2015-10-27 12:04:14','2015-10-27 19:04:14','',0,'http://www.ivsn.org/?p=1574',12,'post','',0),(1575,23,'2015-10-27 11:58:58','2015-10-27 18:58:58','<h1 class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Plan Your Holiday Giving and Volunteering Now!</span></h1>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Generous support from the community during the holiday season is vital to creating a warm and meaningful experience </span><span class=\"s1\">for thousands of homeless adults and children in IVSN programs. Start planning now for ways you can help this year!</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Questions? Contact our Volunteer Associate Jessie Ellington at <a href=\"mailto:jellington@ivsn.org\"><span class=\"s2\">jellington@ivsn.org</span></a> or (650) 685-5880 ext. 180.<img class=\"wp-image-1504 alignnone\" src=\"http://www.ivsn.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Carolands-Holiday-Party_Children.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"300\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n<hr align=\"center\" noshade=\"noshade\" size=\"1\" width=\"100%\" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h2>Give</h2>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>Give a Financial Contribution</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">IVSN relies on generous financial support from the community. Your gift ensures that we may continue to provide high quality, effective services year-round. <a href=\"http://ivsn.wpengine.com/donate/\">Donate Now</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>Donate in Honor of a Friend or Family Member</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p2\">Make a financial donation to IVSN in honor of a loved one. We will mail the honoree a special ho